<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CDU Official Opposes Giving Moscow Too Much for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- A leading foreign affairs expert
in German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's party today cautioned against
giving Russia too much in the way of compensation for NATO's
planned eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
"Russian attempts to make advance in fields not closely related
to security are not very helpful," Karl Lamers, the parliamentary
foreign policy spokesman of Kohl's Christian Democratic alliance
(CDU/CSU), said as quoted by the German press agency.
</P>
<P>
Lamers said Moscow's bid to link acceptance of the NATO
enlargement to conversion of the Group of Seven club of rich
industrial nations into a G-8 with Russia was a mistaken attempt.
</P>
<P>
He added that NATO should respect the legitimate security
interests of Russia, but the question remained whether such
concerns were caused by the West or arose more from developments
in the East and the South as was often stated by military
officials in Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
