<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-24 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Deports Alleged Iraqi Secret Agent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's military court
decided today to deport an Iraqi citizen who was taken into
custody one week ago for alleged links with Iraq's intelligence
service.
</P>
<P>
In a verdict issued in the name of assistant military
prosecutor Judge Khalid Hammoud, the military court announced
the "deportation of Bassam Yaaqoub Yousef, 28, from Lebanon
after a complete of investigation."
</P>
<P>
The court asked the Directorate of Public Security to
implement the deportation, after interrogating the defendant,
hearing witnesses and study of the file, the verdict said.
</P>
<P>
The verdict accused Bassam of "illegally" entering Lebanon, but
noted that Bassam "is not a Lebanese and does not reside
in Lebanon and therefore can not be tried on the Lebanese
land."
</P>
<P>
Bassam was arrested in Lebanon on February 16 on charges that he
participated in operations of killing opponents of Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein in Britain, Kuwait, Lebanon and Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Judicial sources said Bassam, a rich Christian from
Mosul in northern Iraq, was working for the Iraqi intelligence
service.
</P>
<P>
The anonymous sources said that he had entered Lebanon
several times with a fake Egyptian passport under the name of
Saleh Salem.
</P>
<P>
They said that a Lebanese woman, whose name was withheld,
was detained with Bassam.
</P>
<P>
The detained Iraqi reportedly made confessions that he had
been ordered by the Iraqi intelligence service to assassinate
Iraqi dissidents in Lebanon and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
But he denied these confessions later, arguing that he
wrote the letters and documents which linked him to the Iraqi
intelligence service so as to win the sympathy of a Lebanese
woman he loved.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Lebanese government released and deported
three Iraqi diplomats suspected of killing a leading Iraqi
dissident in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The release of the Iraqis ended a nearly three-year-old case,
which prompted Lebanon and Iraq to sever their diplomatic
ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
