<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Larry Flynt" Takes Top Award at Berlin Film Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Milos Forman's controversial
"The People vs. Larry Flynt" (U.S.) won the Golden Bear award at
closing ceremonies today of the two-week 47th Berlin Film
Festival, with top acting awards going to Leonardo DiCaprio and
Juliette Binoche.
</P>
<P>
DiCaprio took the Silver Bear for best actor for his title role
in "William Shakespeare's Romeo and Juliet" (U.S.), with his
female counterpart being Binoche, who portrayed a love-struck
nurse in "The English Patient" (U.S.).
</P>
<P>
Best Director honors went to Eric Heumann for "Port Djema"
(France). The jury, headed by former French Cultural Minister Jack
Lang, gave its annual special jury award to the film "He Liu" (The
River) from Taiwan, China, which also took the Silver Bear prize.
</P>
<P>
Other awards included a special Silver Bear for Franco-Chilean
director Raoul Ruiz' "Genealogies d'un Crime" (France) and a prize
for outstanding individual achievement to Zbigniew Preisner for
his screenplay for "The Island on Birdstreet"
(Denmark/Britain/Germany).
</P>
<P>
Forman has been nominated for an Oscar in the best director
category at the U.S. Academy Awards ceremonies in March, and Woody
Harrelson for a best actor Oscar for his portrayal of "Hustler"
magazine publisher Flynt.
</P>
<P>
A great success at the Berlin festival, the film has been
controversial elsewhere. In the United States, the movie was
condemned by feminists and a number of leading columnists, while
Columbia Pictures and Phoenix Pictures published full-page
advertisements in The New York Times and The Los Angeles Times to
defend it.
</P>
<P>
The European version of its promotional poster, with Harrelson
swaddled in an American flag and "crucified" over the loins of a
naked woman, was banned last week by authorities in Marseille,
France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
