<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-24 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranians to Stage Demonstrations During Hajj </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran declared here today that
Iranian pilgrims will stage political demonstrations during the
forthcoming hajj rituals in Mecca, Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by Mohammad Reyshahri, head of Iranian
hajj pilgrims and representative of Iranian Supreme Leader Ali
Khamenei and carried in all evening Persian dailies.
</P>
<P>
Reyshahri, also one of the four nominees for the 7th
presidential race scheduled for June, claimed that Mecca and hajj
must be the starting point for public uprising in the world of
Islam.
</P>
<P>
He said that hajj must be used as an instrument of
strengthening the power of Islamic leadership.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported earlier that about
100,000 Iranian pilgrims will leave for Mecca and Medina for hajj in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi government bans all political activities during the
pilgrimage. After the Islamic revolution in Iran in 1979, Iranian
pilgrims insisted on staging political demonstrations and rallies,
saying that the pilgrimage should be used for political aims.
</P>
<P>
Iranian pilgrims clashed with Saudi police in a political
demonstration near the grand mosque in the holy city of Mecca on
July 31, 1987. Some 320 Iranians were killed in the bloody Mecca
incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
