<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lufthansa Ordered to Cut Domestic Fare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The German airline Lufthansa was
formally ordered today by anti-monopoly watchdogs to reduce its
high fare on route between capital Berlin and the financial center
of Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Cartel Office issued the order following a written
warning. It told the airline that its one-way fare on this route
could not exceed by more than Deutsche 10 marks (5.928 U.S.
dollars) the price of the Berlin-Munich flight, a longer distance.
</P>
<P>
Lufthansa is now the sole airline flying the lucrative
Berlin-Frankfurt route. The Cartel Office noted that Lufthansa
charged on the route much more than on others where there was
competition, mainly from Deutsche BA, a unit of British Airways.
</P>
<P>
It described such a price disparity as a breach of German
competition law.
</P>
<P>
Lufthansa indicated that it would challenge the office's ban on
its higher Berlin-Frankfurt charges. It was entitled under German
law to set a high price because of the loss of money on domestic
routes for several years, it stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to the authorities, companies in a monopoly position
have no fundamental right to charge whatever it takes to cover
their costs, and Lufthansa is profitable overall.
</P>
<P>
Lufthansa said that, however, would it cut Berlin-Frankfurt
fares, it would lose money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
