<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Urged to Tighten Fiscal Policy: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The British government should
tighten its fiscal policy soon to avoid the risk of suffering a
"boom and bust" cycle, a report published today by the accountant
Coopers &AMP; Lybrand warned.
</P>
<P>
The report came after Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth
Clarke's warning Sunday in a BBC interview that it would be
damaging to cut interest rates to try to stem the strength of the
sterling. That would cause high inflation.
</P>
<P>
The report said that although the immediate outlook for
Britain's economy is favorable, strong consumer demand and the
improving housing market mean interest rates might need to
increase sharply unless the government raises taxes or cuts public
spending soon.
</P>
<P>
However, it warned that higher rates could push the economy
into recession by the turn of the century, so it called for a net
tax increase or a spending cut of 5-10 billion pounds (8-16
billion US dollars) over the next two years "to put the public
finances on a sounder footing." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
