<HEADLINE> US Secretary of State Achieves Objectives of China Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Visiting US Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright told a news conference tonight that she has
achieved the objectives of her China tour.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of her visit is to demonstrate continuity of the
Clinton administration's policy of comprehensive engagement with
China and President Clinton's determination to strengthen US-China
Relations, she said.
</P>
<P>
She was also interested in developing personal relationship
with Chinese leaders, which would help to advance areas of shared
interests and bridge differences between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"My visit here reaffirmed America's commitment to strategic
dialogue with Beijing," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said that she was gratified with the warm reception she
received from the Chinese leaders during the brief trip.
</P>
<P>
Discussing her today's meetings with Chinese President Jiang
Zemin, Premier Li Peng and Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen, she said, the two sides exchanged views on issues of
nuclear non-proliferation, human rights, bilateral trade ties,
environmental protection and the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident, based on these meetings, that the vigorous
strategic dialogue that is developing between the United States
and China will continue." she added.
</P>
<P>
According to the secretary of state, the two countries agreed
today that experts talks on nuclear non-proliferation will be held
in Beijing in mid-March this year.
</P>
<P>
She said that the US side was pleased to see the recent
progress on US-China textile trade and China's enforcement of
protection of intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
The US side will continue to be committed to promoting China's
entry into the World Trade Organization, she said.
</P>
<P>
"I made clear (during the meetings) the continuity of our
one-China policy, our adherence to the three US-China joint
communiques, our unofficial relations with the people of Taiwan,
and our expectation that there will be a peaceful resolution of
the Taiwan issue," she noted. 
</P>
