<HEADLINE> Lufthansa Ordered to Cut Berlin-Frankfurt Fare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- German airline Lufthansa was
formally ordered today by anti-monopoly watchdogs to reduce its
high fare on route between capital Berlin and the financial center
of Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Cartel Office issued the order following a written
warning, and told the airline that its one-way fare on this route
could not exceed by more than 10 marks the price of the
Berlin-Munich flight, a longer distance.
</P>
<P>
The Cartel Office noted that Lufthansa charged on the route
much more than on others where there was competition, mainly from
Deutsche BA, a unit of British Airways.
</P>
<P>
Lufthansa is now the sole airline flying the lucrative
Berlin-Frankfurt route. It has indicated that it would challenge
the office's ban, stressing that it is entitled under German law
to set a high price because of the loss of money on domestic
routes for several years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
