<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Preparatory Committee Members Meet in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- A panel for working out
methods for the selection of the first Legislative Council of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) held its first
meeting here on February 23 and 24.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the meeting, more than 40 Hong Kong and mainland
members of the panel under the Preparatory Committee for the HKSAR
stood in silent tribute to mourn for the death of Deng Xiaoping
who put forward the concept of "one country, two systems" for the
solution to the Hong Kong issue.
</P>
<P>
The meeting briefed the participants on suggestions raised by
the special group for political affairs under the Preliminary
Working Committee of the Preparatory Committee for the Hong Kong
SAR concerning the specific methods for the first legislature of
the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
Based on these suggestions, the participants discussed the
guiding principles for formulating the legislative council, the
requirements for candidates and specific methods for drawing up
geographical constituencies, functional constituencies and the
election committee.
</P>
<P>
They also exchanged views on how to make sure that the
proportion of the legislature members who are of non-Chinese
nationality or have the right of abode in foreign countries does
not surpass 20 percent in the Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
Most of them agreed with the view of the political affairs
group on geographical constituencies -- that the so-called "one
seat, one vote" will not reflect the principle of fair and
balanced involvement, but will make the legislature lack
representativeness.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, they held that if the constituencies are too small
the legislature members to be elected will find it difficult to
reflect general social interests.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to further study the method of multiple seats with
one vote and of selecting representatives according to proportion.
</P>
<P>
The panel members held that functional groups and election
methods prevalent during the election of the Hong Kong Legislative
Council in 1991 will remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
According to a decision by the National People's Congress, the
Preparatory Committee will be responsible for formulating specific
methods for the establishment of the first Legislative Council,
and the Provisional Legislative Council of the Hong Kong SAR will
draw up corresponding ordinance on elections based on these
methods.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided that the panel will solicit opinions from
the Hong Kong people of all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
Lu Ping, vice-chairman and secretary-general of the Preparatory
Committee, attended the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
