<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kohl Faces Showdown Over Tax Reform With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Facing record high unemployment
and widespread pessimism over Germany's economic outlook, German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl today opened talks with leaders of the
opposition Social Democrats in a bid to forge a compromise on the
controversial tax reform.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, who described the planned tax reform as "vital for the
German economy," said he expected from the talks "an important
signal of the determination and ability to reform in Germany."
</P>
<P>
The Free Democratic Party (FDP), the junior partner in Kohl's
ruling coalition, also pressed for a swift decision on the tax
reform. "When the decision is made quickly and clearly motivated,
I'll expect a better situation on the job market from this
summer," FDP leader Wolfgang Gerhardt said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Aimed at reducing tax rates and bolstering business
competitiveness and job creation, tax reform has become the German
government's top domestic policy priority and its main recipe to
curb unemployment, which stands at 4.66 billion, the highest since
1933.
</P>
<P>
The tax reform plan, however, met with sharp criticism from the
Social Democrat Party (SPD). SPD parliamentary leader Rudolf
Scharping called it "scandalous" and "obscene" as the government
was again trying to dip further into the pockets of normal
employees while offering more tax breaks for the rich.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated Sunday that the SPD will not relent in its
opposition to crucial elements of the government's tax reform
plan.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed tax reform, the government plans to cut
income taxes to 15 percent for low-wage earners and 39 percent for
people with high incomes instead of the current marginal rates
ranging from 25.9 percent to 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to government estimates, the income tax cuts, along
with other cuts in corporate tax rates, would leave a shortfall in
state revenue of 44 billion Deutsche marks (26.3 billion U.S.
dollars) which the government wants to reduce to 30 billion marks
(17.9 billion dollars) by raising the 15 percent value-added tax
(VAT) to 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the SPD rejects any VAT increase and has also said that
while it backs cutting income tax for low-wage earners, it wants
to leave the 53 percent rate intact for the rich.
</P>
<P>
The opposition is also strongly against a government proposal
for tax hikes on work done on Sundays, public holidays or at
night.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the SPD wants the entire tax reform package to be
implemented in 1998, instead of 1999 as favored by the government.
</P>
<P>
The government needs to strike a compromise with the SPD if the
reform plan is to survive the upper house of the German
parliament, Bundesrat, where the SPD controls a majority.
</P>
<P>
The government's position in the talks has also been weakened
by infighting within Kohl's own party, the Christian Democratic
Union (CDU). It had to delay last week a parliament vote to
abolish the so-called local business tax due to continued
opposition by eastern German members of the CDU.
</P>
<P>
Today's high-level meeting between the government and the
opposition is expected to yield nothing concrete but rhetoric,
German media commented. The real work is expected to be handed off
to a cluster of expert committees. Sharping said he hoped that
talks would not extend beyond April or May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
