<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Think-Tank Attacks UK Government Claim on Employment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 24 (Xinhua) - Britain's falling unemployment
is a result of structural changes in the economy and has little to
do with government policies, according to a report published today
by an independent think-tank.
</P>
<P>
The report, by the Employment Policy Institute (EPI), argued
that the British labor market has become more flexible because of
structural shifts such as the move to part-time work which began
50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
It undermined the government's claim that
Conservative-instigated deregulation of the labor market is
responsible for the unexpected falling joblessness which is now
below 2 million, dropping by a third since the recent recession.
</P>
<P>
The EPI pointed out that the government should be responsible
for the "deep-rooted and institutional failure" to tackle core
unemployment which has created an underclass of people with slim
prospects of finding work.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report challenged the government's claim that
Britain's job record has made it the envy of other European
countries like Germany, where unemployment has reached levels not
seen since the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
It argued that Germany's jobs crisis has more to do with the
strict anti-inflation policy that accompanied unification and the
economic stringency needed to meet the Maastricht criteria for
European economic and monetary union than with inflexible
employment practices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
