<HEADLINE> Concerns Ease Over Anthrax Outbreak In Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Australia's Victoria State
authorities said today that the crisis over an anthrax outbreak in
the state's north area during the past month appeared to have
eased.
</P>
<P>
"It seems as though there is not much activities in terms of
getting increasing numbers of properties," State Natural Resources
and Environment Department chief veterinary officer Andrew Turner
told reporters in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
Only one new property with anthrax was reported yesterday and
one newly infected animal found, a press release said.
</P>
<P>
Turner attributed the slowdown in the spread of the disease to
the fact that 40 to 50 out of about 79 infected properties had
passed the 10-day threshold for the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
The anthrax outbreak is centered at Tatura-Stanhope area 182 km
north of Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
Turner admitted that scientists were still mystified as to the
cause of the outbreak and that epidemiological investigations were
continuing.
</P>
<P>
Since the first case was discovered on January 26, a total of
160 cows and three sheep have died of the disease.  
</P>
</TEXT>
