<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Officials Question Russians on Talks Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- NATO officials questioned
Russian senior officials today about the texts of Russia's four
proposals on future relations presented to the alliance during
negotiations between NATO and Russia
</P>
<P>
The meeting between NATO Secretary General Javier Solana and
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov Sunday evening was the
second round of talks between NATO and Russia to outline a
document governing all the aspects of future NATO-Russian
relations.
</P>
<P>
The papers, according to NATO sources who asked to remain
anonymous, contained "idea and draft elements" covering the
principles of the new relationship, the mechanism for NATO-Russia
consultations, NATO enlargement and changes in the NATO structure.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Gebhardt von Moltke, NATO assistant
secretary-general for political affairs, met with Russian
Assistant Foreign Minister Nikolai Afanasievsky and a Russian arms
control specialist today to clarify the proposals and ask a number
of questions.
</P>
<P>
Von Moltke was expected to travel to Moscow with NATO's
responds early next month prior to a third Solana-Primakov
negotiating session.
</P>
<P>
The Russians appear to share NATO's thinking in three areas,
the sources said, including the basic principles of a special
relationship, the idea of creating a new NATO-Russia council for
close consultations, and on areas where Russia and NATO can
cooperate, such as in peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agree, sources said, that the new council would be a
distinct body apart from NATO, with its own secretariat, and in
which both sides would have equal status. NATO insists, however,
that Russia will be given a voice but "no veto."
</P>
<P>
During Sunday's talks, Moscow insisted that no significant
defense equipment should be moved onto the territory of NATO's new
members and the alliance disagreed, saying that NATO should
respect the right and obligation of the new members.
</P>
<P>
Russia also wants a legally binding agreement governing future
relations with NATO, but the alliance is only offering a flexible
politically binding charter.
</P>
<P>
However, both NATO and Russia wish to reach a deal before
NATO's Madrid summit in July, when membership invitations are
expected to be issued to Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
