<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia To Reap A Record Winter Crop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 25 (Xinhua) -- A record 1996-97 winter
harvest of 34.5 million tons in Australia was predicted by the
Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics (ABARE).
</P>
<P>
The chief commodities forecaster of the federal government has
boosted its predictions for this harvest by 2.3 million tons from
32.2 million tons, and that is also four million tons up on the
previous high in 1983-84.
</P>
<P>
Wheat production for 1996-97 was forecast at 23.5 million tons,
up marginally from earlier expectations, following an increase in
both plantings and yields.
</P>
<P>
The Grains Council of Australian (GCA) said the record
production would inject around seven billion Australian dollars
(5.40 billion US dollars) into the Australian economy over the
next 12 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
"For an industry that has been devastated by years of drought,
mouse plagues, frosts, low commodity prices and high interest
rates, growers have finally received the confidence boost they
need to reinvest in their industry," GCA said.
</P>
<P>
According to ABARE, major summer irrigated crops, cotton and
rice, were expected to be particularly bountiful in 1996-97, with
production expected to exceed previous records by 10 and 28
percent respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
