<HEADLINE> Pakistan Plans Package of Incentives for Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Senator Sartaj
Aziz said today that a new incentive package for offshore
exploration was being planned to attract oil exploration companies
to country's vast coastal prospective areas.
</P>
<P>
"The basic strategy of the Nawaz Sharif government will remain
to attract foreign private capital and exploit this potential
fully as quickly as possible by facilitating the process and
improving the market conditions," Aziz, secretary general of
Pakistan Muslim League (N), said while addressing the "Pakistan
Oil and Gas Summit 1997."
</P>
<P>
He said the present government would construct massive
infrastructure at Gawadar for a free port and hoped it would help
increase trade with Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to revive industrial sector in a very short time," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He said the government plans to provide a framework to assist
the industry so as to solve problems concerning duties and taxes,
access to the prospective areas, weaknesses in infrastructure,
procedural delays and difficulties in accessing technical data.
</P>
<P>
The former finance minister said oil and gas industry of
Pakistan has remained a cornerstone of his party's economic
strategies.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the summit, the third major event on the subject of
promoting private participation in the petroleum sector of
Pakistan, would result in further improvement in the government's
policies and more importantly in promoting the opportunities for
investment in the sector.
</P>
<P>
He said the private sector has taken the lead in the current
conference while the earlier two conferences were convened by the
government.
</P>
<P>
"It is quite indicative of the changing scenario in which the
private sector is to play the major role in the industrial
development in Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
He voiced the confidence that the three-day conference will
provide a much needed platform for promoting understanding between
the private investors and the key figures of the government, which
would ultimately culminate in practical business in the days to
come. 
</P>
