<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Reiterates Stand on Relations with Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait today reiterated
that easing of relations with Iraq was out of the question
as Baghdad still refused to set free the 620 Kuwaiti
Prisoners of War (POWs) it said still jailed in Iraqi
prisons.
</P>
<P>
However, Kuwait indicated that ties with other countries that
supported Iraq during the Gulf War would be back on track.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Foreign Ministry Undersecretary Sulaiman Majed
Al-Shahin, on the eve of the six anniversary of Kuwaiti liberation
from the seven-month Iraqi occupation on February 26, said that the
Iraqi occupation of Kuwait should not be treated lightly and
its consequences could not fall under the saying "let bygones
be bygones."
</P>
<P>
He said in a statement that "things must be put right
and matters should settle down under just principles."
</P>
<P>
Shahin said that Iraq should treat the question of the
Kuwaiti detainees from a humanitarian angle without exploiting
for in political ends.
</P>
<P>
Iraq should be committed to releasing all information about
the POWs, he said, the Iraqi claims that it holds no prisoners shows
it has no intention to cooperate on this humanitarian issue.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has been insisting that all the POWs detained by
Baghdad be released. But Iraq claimed it has no information
about the persons still missing.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said the Kuwaitis arrested during the occupation were
taken to jails in the southern city of Basra. But these jails
were overrun during the Shiite Muslim uprising that raged in the
months after the Gulf War and all trace of them vanished.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi and Kuwaiti officials sit down together three or four
times a year in Geneva and every month on the Kuwaiti-Iraq
border to try to uncover the fate of those still missing,
but progress has been very slow.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has offered to normalize ties with other Gulf Arab states,
which have been strained since Baghdad's invasion of Kuwait in
1990. Oman and Qatar have improved ties with Baghdad but others
such as Saudi Arabia and Kuwait reject direct dealings with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shahin said that "Iraq remains an aggressive and
hostile element which undermines stability. Kuwait is a victim
and, like other countries, must preserve and protect its
security and stability with every available means."
</P>
<P>
Regarding relations with other countries that stood on the
side of Iraq during the Gulf War, Al-Shahin said that
"Kuwait has not severed relations with any of the countries
which backed Iraq during the invasion and our job is to
neutralize their policies and win their support."
</P>
<P>
Bilateral relations have not been interrupted with Jordan and
there is an honest desire to put the relations back on track, he
said.
</P>
<P>
On ties with Sudan, he said Kuwait has maintained relations with
Khartoum at the level of Charge D'affaires.
</P>
<P>
He also indicated that ties with Yemen might also be improved
although he expressed regret that the country was the only one in
the then U.N. Security Council to take a different stand from
other council members during the occupation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
