<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen Meets Japan's Former Health Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said here today that practical steps
are needed to carry out the decisions of the Manila meeting
between Chinese and Japanese leaders.
</P>
<P>
Qian made the remark during a meeting with Japan's former
Health and Welfare Minister Keigo Ouchi, who is on a good-will
visit at the invitation of the China-Japan Friendship Association.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the Chinese and Japanese peoples should carry on
their friendship from generation to generation, which is a
conclusion drawn from history.
</P>
<P>
He added that the key to this goal is to face history properly,
draw lessons from it and educate the younger generation.
</P>
<P>
Qian said Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto has made
speeches on many occasions making it clear that Japan attaches
importance to developing its relations with China. The Chinese
government welcomed his stance, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that he regarded it as a must that the two countries
carry out the decisions agreed upon by Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and the Japanese prime minister through concrete measures.
</P>
<P>
The two neighboring countries are important to each other, Qian
held, but their ties bear more than bilateral significance. He
expressed the hope that the two countries would view and develop
their ties from a long-term and strategic perspective.
</P>
<P>
"As 1997 is the 25th anniversary of the normalization of
Sino-Japanese relations," he said, "we hope the two governments
and peoples will make concerted efforts to nurture a healthy,
stable friendship."
</P>
<P>
Qian also thanked Ouchi for his condolences over the death of
Deng Xiaoping. Qian said the Chinese people will turn grief into
strength and continue to take the path of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics that was initiated by Deng. 
</P>
