<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Poor People Drops in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Only 4.5 percent or nine
million of Indonesia's 200 million population is poor, down by
about 7.5 percent from 22 million registered at the end of the 5th
five-year Development Plan period (1989-1994), Antara news agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
This is the result of implementing the underdeveloped village
assistance program, the drive to build prosperous families, and
the loan to help the poor start small businesses, Secretary to the
Coordinating minister for people's welfare Suyono Yahya told a
meeting here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Yahya said that according to a census by the Central Bureau of
Statistics in 1996, the drop in the number of poor people is also
due to an equal distribution of health services, education,
infrastructure and facilities.
</P>
<P>
A person is said to live below the poverty line if he consumes
food containing less than 2,100 calories a day, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that a family is also considered poor if it has four
children and the head of the family only earns a monthly gross
income of 300,000 rupiah (about 130 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said the government has set a target that by the end of the
7th five-year Development Plan (1999-2004), the number of poor
Indonesians shall have dropped to zero.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cash Bonuses on Offer for Athletes Who Breaks World Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 25 (Xinhua) -- World athletics governing body
IAAF said on Tuesday that cash bonuses of 100,000 U.S. dollars
will be on offer for athletes who break world records at the World
Championships this summer.
</P>
<P>
The world record compensation is on top of the prize money the
IAAF is offering for the first time at the championships in Athens
on August 1-10.
</P>
<P>
With 60,000 U.S. dollars in prize money going to first-place
finishers, a gold medal winner who breaks a world record will
pocket a total of 160,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The same world record prizes will be on offer at next year's
World Cup in Johannesburg, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
A scaled-down 50,000 U.S. dollars is on offer at the World
Indoor Championships in Paris on March 7-9.
</P>
<P>
Cash incentives had previously been put up by organizers at
certain individual events but this is the first time the IAAF has
offered rewards for performance.
</P>
<P>
Athletes who break a world record more than once in the course
of an event will only be eligible for one prize and relay teams
share the money among themselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
