<HEADLINE> Islamic Jihad Refuses to Participate in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 25 (Xinhua) -- The Islamic Jihad Movement
has refused to give a positive response to a call made by
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat for a national dialogue
scheduled to take place on February 27 in Nablus, JMCC, a
Palestinian press service based in East Jerusalem, reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a communique addressing the Palestinian people, the
movement complained that "it is impossible for Palestinian
political forces to take part in the national dialogue while many
of their innocent cadres are still locked in the authorities'
prisons due to unjust rules and without trial."
</P>
<P>
The movement also accused the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) of "complying to enemy and responding to its demands for
declaring war against the Islamic and national forces which
insist on struggle against the (enemy) occupation."
</P>
<P>
The communique, issued from Jerusalem and dated on February
24, added that the Islamic Jihad welcomes a dialogue based on
"resisting occupation and not complying or cooperating with it."
</P>
<P>
The movement suggested that the national dialogue be aimed at
uniting Palestinians to confront Israeli schemes of Judaizing
Jerusalem and establishing Jewish settlements. It said that the
national dialogue should not coincide with further negotiations
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
"There is no meaning and use to initiate a dialogue if it
rests on wreckage of the Palestinian legitimate right to
struggle against occupation," the movement declared.
</P>
<P>
Under pressure from the Israeli authorities following a wave
of suicide bombing attacks in February and March last year, the
PNA carried out a crackdown on the Islamic Jihad group and the
Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas).
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of their activists were arrested and many of them are
still in jails. 
</P>
