</P>
<P>
Israeli officials were quoted as saying that during a private
visit to France last month, Foreign Minister David Levy believed
that he had secured a commitment from de Charette to visit for two
or three days,in an attempt to erase misunderstandings left over
from last fall's visit by President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Chirac pushed an Israeli bodyguard, and
spoke in the Palestinian Legislative Council in favor of
Palestinian control of East Jerusalem. Moreover, in the original
program, Chirac was to spend virtually no time at the Western
Wall, while spending time at other religious shrines in the
Old City of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
However, when Levy became aware last week that de Charette
would only visit Israel and Palestinian territory for a day
during a March 4-6 regional swing also involving Syria and
Lebanon, "he flew into a rage," a Foreign Ministry official
said.
</P>
<P>
Levy insisted that the Foreign Ministry summon French
Ambassador Jean Noel de Lacoste to complain.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Ambassador to France Avi Pazner filed a similar
complaint with the French Foreign Ministry, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Yigal Palmor said De Lacoste was
summoned last week to the ministry, where "we expressed our
discontent over changes in the program for the visit."
</P>
<P>
Palmor said Paris had originally promised "a full state visit
of two or three days." "We don't mind what he does in
the region once he is here, but instead of dedicating two or
three days to Israel on a full-scale visit, he will be here
for a 24-hour visit which will include a visit to the
Palestinian Authority," Palmor added.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think we should beg de Charette to visit," one
official said bitterly. "He can stay home. However as Levy
became personally offended, the Foreign Ministry has decided to
file a complaint."
</P>
<P>
Relations between Israel and France have grown sour since the
right-wing Likud Party came to power in elections last
May. France has wanted a bigger say in the peace process, but
Israel has replied no way arguing that France has leaned to the
Arabs too much in its position regarding the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
