<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Business Suffers From Office Theft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 25 (Xinhua) -- German business losts 3 to 20
billion U.S. dollars a year because of office theft, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The losses are still expected to rise by 25 percent by the end
of the century, Manfred Lotze of the German Detective Federation
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that in 1995, shoplifting caused about
6-billion-dollar inventory losses, 25 percent of which were due to
theft by employees.
</P>
<P>
Traders are constantly up against shoplifting, but many bosses
have been found wary of taking any legal action against the
culprits for fear of frightening business partners, customers and
banks.
</P>
<P>
Employees often take home company property, such as pencils or
a stapler, spontaneously or without much thought, but often too,
the thieving is methodical and well-organized and many employees
appear to enjoy the risk of taking things from work.
</P>
<P>
Lotze, head of one of Germany's largest trade detective
agencies, said that in one case his agency found the chief of the
repairs department at an engineering firm taking home components
which he then put together at home and gave the final machine
products to his father-in-law, a market trader, to sell.
</P>
<P>
In another case, warehouse goods were found shipped abroad.
</P>
<P>
It is also reported that office theft often starts with making
private telephone calls at work, and a survey showed that three
out of every four employees make private calls in company time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
