<HEADLINE> Sirens Sounded in Memory of Deng in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 25 (Xinhua) -- A Start ferry, shuttling
between the Hong Kong Island and the Kowloon Peninsula, sounded
its siren at 10:00 sharp this morning in memory of Chinese leader
Deng Xiaoping, who died six days ago in Beijing at the age of 93.
</P>
<P>
Almost at the same time, sirens echoed to the sky across the
Victoria Harbor for one minute, expressing Hong Kong people's
mourning over the death of Deng, who devised the great concept of
"one country, two systems" to make possible that China resumes its
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Fleets under several shipping companies in Hong Kong all
lowered their flags to half-mast and sounded their sirens for one
minute at 10:00 this morning.
</P>
<P>
Like the boats, other public transport means -- buses, trucks
and trains in Hong Kong paid their respects to Deng in various
forms at 10:00 a.m. today, when a memorial meeting attended by
10,000 people started in the Great Hall of the People in Beijing
to mourn over the death of Deng.
</P>
<P>
Solemn music resounded throughout the underground railway
stations for ten minutes, and trains running between Kowloon and
Canton blew their horns at ten o'clock this morning in memory of
Deng.
</P>
<P>
The Peak Tram, a tourist route lifting passengers from the
downtown area of Hong Kong to the Victoria Peak, suspended its
services for one minute at 10:00 a.m. All the 800 vehicles run by
the China Motor Bus, one of Hong Kong's main public services
providers, were decked with white flowers and black ribbons today
to express grief over the passing of Deng. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
