<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half of HK External Trade by Ocean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 25 (Xinhua) -- The value of external trade
by ocean accounted for 48 percent of Hong Kong's total value of
external trade in 1996, according to statistics released by the
Census and Statistics Department today.
</P>
<P>
Another 26 percent was transported by land and yet another 20
percent by air. The remaining 6 percent included shipment by
river, postal parcels and accompanied goods of passengers
traveling by various means of transport.
</P>
<P>
Shipment by ocean amounted to some 1,420 billion HK dollars
(182 billion U.S. dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
The United States remained the largest destination for Hong
Kong's total exports (comprising domestic exports and re-exports)
by ocean, accounting for a share of 31 percent in value terms in
1996.
</P>
<P>
And Japan was the largest supplier of Hong Kong's imports by
ocean, with a share of 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to trade figures published earlier this month, the
territory's re-exports totaled 1,185.8 billion HK dollars (152
billion U.S. dollars) in 1996, 6.6 percent higher than in 1995,
while the value of domestic exports decreased by 8.4 percent to
212.2 billion HK dollars (27.2 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Imports for the entire year recorded a 3-percent increase to
1,536.6 billion HK dollars (197 billion U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
