<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blazes Threat to HK's Old Office Buildings: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Every one in three
commercial buildings in Hong Kong is at huge fire risk, according
to a government study released here Monday.
</P>
<P>
A Buildings Department study revealed that fire is likely to
erupt in one third of the local commercial buildings, in a quarter
of the industrial and a fifth of the residential blocks and other
buildings.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed the number of buildings deteriorating into
potential fire traps was swelling by 1,000 every year.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Department urged that urgent action was needed
to alert owners to the dangers, particularly in the pre-1975
commercial buildings.
</P>
<P>
The most common dangers included fire doors being left open,
substitute materials being used for fire doors, locked emergency
exits and alterations to fire escape routes.
</P>
<P>
A blaze in a commercial building in Yau Ma Tei in November last
year, which was believed to be the worst over the past century in
Hong Kong, killed 39 people and injured 81. And 17 people died in
a karaoke bar blaze in Tsim Sha Tsui last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
