<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improving Supply of Commercial Energy Key to Pak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's President Farooq
Leghari said here today that improving the supply of commercial
energy at an affordable rate is the key to the country's economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The government should make great efforts to narrow the gap
between reserves and estimated potential by exploiting the proven
reserves fully, said Leghari when inaugurating a three-day oil and
gas summit here.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan Oil and Gas Summit 97" was organized by the Ministry
of Petroleum and Natural Resources in cooperation with a number of
oil and gas companies including Shell Pakistan Ltd. and United
Meridian International Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, Leghari said, is gifted with enormous resources which
need to be tapped.
</P>
<P>
"I have no doubt in my mind about the bright future that awaits
Pakistan when its vast resources of men and material are fully
mobilized," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan spends a very large portion of its foreign exchange
earnings on the import of oil and it imported 2 billion U.S.
dollars' worth of oil in fiscal 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
The sum accounted for 23 percent of the country's export
earnings in the fiscal year and it will further go up in view of
the increasing energy needs, Leghari said.
</P>
<P>
The country, he noted, was recently able to revive the
confidence of the oil and gas industry by restoring the duty and
tax concessions which were earlier allowed under the Concession
Agreements executed prior to June 13, 1996.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the decision would convey a clear message to the
international community that the country is not only serious but
also sufficiently flexible in adjusting to market needs and
requirements.
</P>
<P>
The president said that although exploration of oil and gas
started in this part of the world about 140 years ago, Pakistan
has so far drilled fewer than 500 exploratory wells with a success
rate of one discovery in every four exploratory wells.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that by harnessing the breakthroughs in technology,
such as three-dimensional seismic exploration techniques, Pakistan
would be able to discover larger deposits of oil and gas.
</P>
<P>
Leghari said that since 1947 governments had not paid
sufficient attention to developing the country's human and
material resources.
</P>
<P>
This is the reason that Pakistan had not been able to realize
its potential and lagged behind even those countries which
achieved independence after it, he said. Now Pakistan has to make
up for the deficiencies in the past.
</P>
<P>
Leghari urged countries in the region to cooperate in putting
up joint importation proposals and thus help them obtain benefits
of large-scale economy and optional routing of pipelines.
</P>
<P>
A large gas market in Pakistan and in its neighboring countries
would create attractive opportunities for regional projects
leading to a "win-win situation for gas producers, pipeline
sponsors and end users," he said.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 delegates from 28 countries are participating in
the international meeting, the third since 1988.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Pakistan currently consumes 120 million
barrels of oil per annum and demand will rise by 50 percent in the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan targets to double its oil production to 120,000
barrels a day by the end of next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
