<HEADLINE> Americans Win Four-man Bobsleigh Race in World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Brian Shimer, who has two wins
in the two-man series, posted his first win in the four-man race
piloting the U.S.1 team to the middle of the podium at the World
Cup bobsleigh in Nagano. Japan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Shimer, the world bronze medallists with Chip Minton, Randy
Jones and Robert Olesen, clocked 52.71 seconds in the first run
and 53.04 in the second for a combined winning time of 1:45.75.
</P>
<P>
They defeated world silver medallists from Germany, Dirk Wiese,
Christoph Bartsch, Thorsten Weber and Michael Liekmeier by 0.27
seconds, and Frenchmen Bruno Mingeon, Emanuel Hostache, Eric Le
Chanony and Max Robert by 0.32 seconds.
</P>
<P>
It was the sixth-round race originally scheduled to be held at
Calgary, where bad weather forced cancellation. Those who entered
the Calgary round earned points counting towards the overall
standings.
</P>
<P>
The final leg of the seven-round series will be held on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Marcel Rohner, one of the three Swiss pilots who were
disqualified from the world championships for using illegal axles
on their machines, remained top in the standings with 178 points,
following his team's fourth place finish.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the International Bobsleigh Federation
issued a statement, confirming the disqualification of the
Switzerland 1, 2 and 3 teams piloted by Rohner, Reto Goetschi and
Christian Reich -- as they found breaches of international rules
on the front axles of all three sleds and the rear axle of
Rohner's sled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
