<HEADLINE> Inflation Declines in Tanzania: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Inflation in Tanzania
dropped from 30 percent to 14 percent while export earnings
continued to increase from 350 million US Dollars to an estimated
650 million Dollars in the past five years of the economic reform.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed here at the weekend by Minister of State in
the President's Office Nassoro Malocho when speaking at a seminar
of prospective investors from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The state minister added low capacity utilization of
industrial production has improved after economic reforms and
risen from 30 percent to approximately 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
He noted the government for the past ten years has been
executing the economic reform measures aimed at adjusting and
improving socio-economic and institutional capacities.
</P>
<P>
He added the major objectives of the reforms were changing the
then central planned and controlled market and liberalized
economy as a means to achieve sustainable economic growth in the
country.
</P>
<P>
In order to improve the investment climate and create an
enabling enrironment for attracting both domestic and external
investors, measures have been taken to review a number of land,
industrial, minerals and social policies.
</P>
<P>
He assured the investors that the issues on investment policy
and appropriate incentive would be tabled in parliament in April
this year and when approved the Investment Promotion Center will
operate as a one-stop centre, he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in her opening remarks, South African High
Commissioner to Tanzania Thandi Lujabe-Rankoe urged the two
countries to work together to strengthen technological
expertise.
</P>
<P>
She aslo urged them to adopt modern management systems and
marketing capabilities for the mutual benefit of their people.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was attended by Tanzanian Minister for Water Pius
Ngwandu, Minister of State in the Prime Minister's Office
Kingunge Ngomballe-Mwiru, Finance Minister Daniel Yona and other
senior officials, 
</P>
</TEXT>
