<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Seek for 400,000 Vietnamese MIA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam will make efforts to
seek for 400,000 Vietnamese soldiers missing in action during the
Vietnam War, the local press today quoted Prime Minister Vo Van
Kiet as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The remains of all Vietnamese soldiers who died either in
Vietnam or abroad should be recovered and buried in Vietnam's war
cemeteries," said the prime minister when meeting with senior
officials of the Ministry of Labor, War Invalids and Social
Affairs in Hanoi last week.
</P>
<P>
He told the officials that they were responsible for recovering
all the remains of the martyrs for reburial in the war cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
An interim report by the ministry showed that Vietnam lost more
than 1 million soldiers and 2 million civilians in the war of
resistance against the Americans between 1954 and 1975.
</P>
<P>
Statistics issued by the ministry late last year after two
years of surveys put the number of missing Vietnamese soldiers at
400,000.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials said a lack of information and changes of
battlefield landscapes had made it almost impossible to trace even
the graves of fallen combatants who had been buried by their
comrades-in-arms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
