<HEADLINE> Wife of Top Ugandan Rebel Commander Surrenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 25 (Xinhua) -- One of the wives of a top
rebel commander in northern Uganda surrendered to the government
troops, a report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The name of the woman was withheld for security reason, "The
New Vision" said in its report. Her husband, the self-styled
Colonel Alex Otti Lagoni, is commanding one of the three
remaining groups of the Lord's Resistance Army (LRA).
</P>
<P>
The woman surrendered with other 15 LRA rebels with their arms
to the government troops in northern Kitgum District.
</P>
<P>
Alex Otti Lagoni was wounded in a battle recently and
reportedly refused to return to LRA's bases in southern Sudan as
LRA leader Joseph Kony asked. The commander is nursing his wounds
in northern bushes.
</P>
<P>
The rebel LRA had 13 groups and more than 2,000 rebels earlier
last year. But now, it has only three groups operating in northern
Uganda and only hundreds of rebels. Most of its members were
killed or surrendered. enditem


