<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Prime Minister to Visit Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister
Chavalit Yongchaiyudh is scheduled to arrive here Thursday for a
two-day official visit to Malaysia, it was officially announced
here today.
</P>
<P>
During the visit which is part of his tour of countries of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), Chavalit, who
assumed the post in December last year, will hold discussions with
his Malaysian counterpart, Mahathir Mohamad, on bilateral and
regional matters, a Foreign Ministry statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai prime minister will be granted an audience by Supreme
Head of State Tuanku Ja'afar.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit, to be accompanied by a 42-member delegation, is also
scheduled to meet representatives of the Malaysian private sector
to discuss investment opportunities in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Both Malaysia and Thailand are ASEAN members.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thailand's newly-appointed ambassador to Malaysia,
Suchitra Hiranprueck, said in an interview with Malaysia's
official news agency Bernama that Chavalit's visit would also be
an opportunity for leaders of both sides to look into ways to
resolve a few existing problems including those involving the
common border.
</P>
<P>
The discussions are also expected to center on better trade and
investment promotion between the two countries, Suchitra, who
assumed her post here on February 20, said. "Although we are
neighbors," she added, "I think our trade and economic relations
have not been so extensive. There's still room for improvement."
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is Thailand's second largest trading partner in the
ASEAN whose members also include Brunei, Indonesia, Singapore, the
Philippines and Vietnam. But the total value of their trade is
still small, accounting for only 4 percent of Thailand's total
global trade in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade stood at 13.075 billion ringgit (about 5.23
billion U.S. dollars) from January to November last year, of which
Thailand's exports to Malaysia were 4.631 billion ringgit (about
1.85 billion dollars) against its imports of 8.444 billion ringgit
(about 3.38 billion dollars) from Malaysia, according to
preliminary figures available.  
</P>
</TEXT>
