<HEADLINE> Japanese Boxing to Take New Safety Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Japan's boxing governing body
will take new safety measures after one professional boxer died
after a bout and another needed brain surgery.
</P>
<P>
Junior welterweight Hiroyuki Hiranuma, 24, died of an acute
hematoma of the brain late Monday, two weeks after collapsing into
a coma at the end of an eight-round bout, commission officials
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Hiranuma, who was not knocked to the ground during the bout,
was the 30th Japanese to die from injuries sustained in boxing.
</P>
<P>
Toshihiro Tsuda, 25, underwent brain surgery on Monday
immediately after falling unconscious, after the referee stepped
in to save him from a flurry of punches in the final round of
another eight-round junior welterweright bout. 
</P>
