<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior S. Korean Presidential Secretaries Intend to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 25 (Xinhua) -- All senior South Korean
presidential secretaries, including Chief Presidential Secretary
Kim Kwang-il, expressed their intention today to quit their posts
"for their failure to serve their chief executive well."
</P>
<P>
The 12 officials told President Kim Young-sam of their intent
at a luncheon meeting following Kim's nationally-televised speech
earlier in the day apologizing to the public for Hanbo Business
Group's bribe-for-loan scandal.
</P>
<P>
Kim Kwang-il said that he and his colleagues are stepping down
"as we are totally responsible for not properly assisting the
president," according to Presidential Spokesman Yoon Yeo-joon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ruling New Korea Party (NKP) Chairman Lee Hong-koo
and other key NKP officials also expressed their intention today
to resign from their posts to President Kim.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Prime Minister Lee Soo-sung and the
entire cabinet are expected to tender their resignations later
this week, according to an official at the prime minister's office.
</P>
<P>
In his speech today, President Kim, marking the fourth
anniversary of his presidency, revealed his plan to conduct a
reshuffle of his presidential staff, the ruling party leadership
and the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Kim publicly apologized to the nation for the Hanbo loan
scandal, saying that he assumes responsibility for the scandal in
which his close aides are also involved.
</P>
<P>
The Hanbo loan scandal surfaced following the bankrupcy of
Hanbo Iron and Steel Company, the flagship firm of South Korea's
14th largest group Hanbo Business Group, on January 23 after
failing to honor billions of U.S. dollars in notes.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution said that Hanbo Business Group General Chairman
Chung Tae-soo used huge amounts of money to bribe important
figures in the process of financing his pet project to build
Tangin Steel Mill in South Korea's South Chungchong Province.
</P>
<P>
So Far, 10 people, including three legislators of the ruling
party, one legislator of the main opposition National Congress for
New Politics (NCNP), and one minister, have been indicted by the
prosecution for graft or influence peddling.
</P>
<P>
Chung, who was also indicted on fraud and embezzlement charges,
had secured six billion U.S. dollars in bank loans between 1992
and 1996 without sufficient collateral for his Hanbo Iron and
Steel Company. 
</P>
