<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Deploys F-18 Fighters in Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 25 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
started deploying F-18 fighter jets in Kuwait to replace eight
radar-evading F-117a Stealth bombers, Kuwaiti military sources
said today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the bombers dispatched to Kuwait last
year as a safeguard against what it figured as a possible Iraqi
attack were being pulled out and the first of a batch of advanced
F-18 fighters had already arrived, but no figure of how many F-18
fighters would be deployed here is available.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. aircraft carrier Kitty Hawk also will be leaving the
Gulf soon. It would be replaced by about 30 F-15 and F-16
fighters that began arriving in Qatar from the United States as
part of an air expeditionary force, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The rotation coincides with the deployment of an armored
battalion in Kuwait for three months of training. About 1,200
U.S. troops have arrived in Kuwait to take part in routine
exercises with the Kuwaiti military. The soldiers are now
training at the Udairi desert range, some 50 kilometers from the
Iraqi border.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. usually rotates a troop battalion through Kuwait
since 1994 when tension was intensified here following Iraqi
troop's movement in the south near Kuwaiti border. The troops
use equipment stockpiled at Camp Doha, 25 kilometers to the west
of Kuwait City, to conduct regular training exercises with the
Kuwaiti forces.
</P>
<P>
This time, the troops will take part in a series of
exercises, codenamed Intrinsic Action 97, which will last four
months and include live fire training and joint maneuvers with
the Kuwaiti army, U.S. army spokesman Lieutenant Colonel Thomas
Nickerson said.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait signed defense pacts with the United States, Britain
and France after the Gulf War and Kuwaiti military forces
regularly holds exercises with forces from the three western
countries.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Kuwait Ryan Crocker renewed U.S. commitment
Sunday to Kuwait's security and stability against any outside
threat.
</P>
<P>
He said in a statement on Kuwait's Independence and
Liberation days, observed today and Wednesday, that "we will
continue to maintain a strong U.S. presence in the region in
order to deter Saddam (Hussain)."
</P>
<P>
"As long as Kuwait feels the need for support, we will
provide it," Crocker said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
