<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Spy for Kremlin Exposed to Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 25 (Xinhua) -- A spy, who worked for
Kremlin and is serving a 15-year sentence in Israel, was exposed
Tuesday night to the public after the Israeli Supreme Court lifted
a ban on publication of the affair.
</P>
<P>
Today's Jerusalem Post said that the ban was lifted at the
state's request so the case could serve as a precedent in
determining heavy sentences for espionage.
</P>
<P>
Roman Weisfeld, 55, who sent Israel's secrets by Morse code to
the National Security Committee of the former Soviet Union, or the
KGB, was recruited by the KGB in 1976 with the purpose of making
aliya (immigration) in order to collect military and political
information about Israel.
</P>
<P>
He underwent a period of training in various espionage
techniques and in 1980 was sent on his mission to collect
information about Israel's relations with Arab states, the United
States, and the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
In return, Weisfeld received large sums of money and was
promised an apartment in the Commonwealth of the Independent
States (CIS) if he wished to return.
</P>
<P>
Weisfeld, an electrical engineer, found himself a job with
the Elco company in Haifa in northern Israel, a job which
eventually gained him access to one of Israel's main air bases.
</P>
<P>
He succeeded in having maintained contact with his operators
in the KGB for five years with the use of Morse code.
</P>
<P>
In November 1985, Weisfeld went to Vienna, Austria, where he
met one of his operators, from whom he received 3,000
U.S. dollars as well as more sophisticated equipment.
</P>
<P>
It was after this visit that Weisfeld began his work as a
company representative on the air base, where he was able to
collect data on the types and movements of aircraft, and
information of the organization of the squadrons, and the storage
of weaponry.
</P>
<P>
This continued for more than two years.
</P>
<P>
In April 1988, Weisfeld was instructed to meet his operator
again in Europe, this time in Berlin, but there was a hitch and
the meeting did not take place.
</P>
<P>
Shortly afterwards, he was arrested, tried, and found guilty
by Israel's Tel Aviv District Court of aggravated espionage, and
was sentenced to 15 years' imprisonment, after an appeal to the
Supreme Court was rejected.
</P>
<P>
There have been unconfirmed reports of the arrest of other
new immigrants on suspicion of spying, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
