<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Becomes Oil Products Exporter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Thailand, traditionally an oil
products importer, has now become an exporter, with a surplus
refining capacity forcing local refiners to export excess output
of oil products.
</P>
<P>
The volume of oil products exported by local refiners reached
an average of 107,619 barrels per day (b/d) or 17.1 million liters
in January, according to a report from the Department of
Commercial Registration of the Thai government available here
today.
</P>
<P>
The top export was high-speed diesel oil, with exports of 40
million liters a day. Gasoline followed at 8.8 million liters per
day, aviation fuel 3.4 million liters per day and liquefied
petroleum gas (LPG) 400 metric tons per day.
</P>
<P>
The output of the products in January soared 57 percent over
the same period of last year to reach an average of 811,057 b/d.
</P>
<P>
The jump was due largely to the start of operation last year of
two new oil refineries in the country. The two oil refineries are
run by Rayong Refining Co. (RRC) and Star Petroleum Refining Co.
(SPRC).
</P>
<P>
RRC and SPRC, with a crude processing capacity of 145,000 b/d
and 130,000 b/d respectively, have significantly boosted imports
of crude and sharply slashed those of refined products.
</P>
<P>
As a result, imports of finished oil products in January
dropped 71 percent to 43,401 b/d, with those of gasoline plunging
73 percent and diesel 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
Domestic demand for oil products in the month increased 8
percent to an average of 720,787 b/d or 114.6 million liters per
day, with consumption of gasoline up 6 percent, diesel oil 17
percent and LPG 12 percent and fuel oil down 7 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
