<HEADLINE> S. Korean President Apologizes for Corruption Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Apologizing for a major loan
scandal, South Korean President Kim Young-sam said today that he
will bar one of his sons from social activities for his alleged
involvement.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a televised address on the fourth anniversary of
his inauguration, Kim said that "I, as the president, offer a
sincere apology to the people" over the scandal swirling around
the failed Hanbo Steel Company.
</P>
<P>
Hanbo Steel, the flagship of the Hanbo Group, went bankrupt on
January 23 after racking up 5.8 billion U.S. dollars in debt. The
debt was incurred mostly in government-controlled bank loans,
which Hanbo secured after giving bribes.
</P>
<P>
"What troubles me more is that the name of one of my sons is
talked about in connection with this case," Kim said in his
address.
</P>
<P>
His second son, Hyun-chul, has been accused by opposition
parties of taking huge kickbacks for helping Hanbo buy foreign
equipment and technology with government loans. He was questioned
over the weekend but was later cleared of the suspicion.
</P>
<P>
But the president said that he still felt morally responsible
and will order his son to quit all social activities.
</P>
<P>
The son, aged 38, heads a socially active fraternity group. He
holds no government position but has been criticized by the
opposition for alleged influence-peddling.
</P>
<P>
State prosecutors last week also indicted 10 people, including
a Cabinet minister, politicians from the ruling and opposition
parties, top banker and the founder of the Hanbo Group, the
nation's 14th largest conglomerate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
