<HEADLINE> Thailand's LPG Output Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's production of
processed liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) rose by 23 percent last
year to a daily average of 5,155 metric tons, according to the
Department of Commercial Registration today.
</P>
<P>
The increase was due to additional LPG production capacity in
three plants, one in the south and two in the east.
</P>
<P>
The higher production exceeded local consumption which stood at
4,634 tons a day last year, allowing 538 tons a day to be exported
to neighboring countries, including Laos and Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
This year, domestic LPG demand is expected to rise by 18
percent to a daily average of 5,488 tons, of which 5,128 tons will
be used as fuel, up 20 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Local LPG production is expected to soar by about 55.8 percent
to 8,029 tons a day this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
