<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banking Institute Set up in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 25 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya School of Monetary
Studies (KSMS) was set up in Nairobi with its focus on the
training of specialist economists for the eastern and southern
African region.
</P>
<P>
The institute established by the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK)
admitted its first group of 600 students last month who are
scheduled to learn, among other things, high level economics,
professional banking, data processing and management courses.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to present the school's prospectus, CBK
Governor Micah Cheserem said that the school is aimed at training
specialist economists to formulate, implement and sustain
policies for economic growth for Kenya and the region as well.
</P>
<P>
Cheserem, who is the school master, noted that resources in
Africa are underutilized because of a shortage of economists who
could formulate electric economic policies.
</P>
<P>
The school will focus sharply on practically-oriented
training, analytical skills and quantitative methods required by
the emerging economies to sustain the current and future economic
reforms, he added.
</P>
<P>
During the first public lecture at the school last week, the
Deputy Director of the CBK, Nzioki Kibua, said that the school
will strive to respond to the lack of specialist economists.
</P>
<P>
The banking school targets financial houses in the region,
government ministries, the public and private sectors, regional
and multinational organizations, he added.
</P>
<P>
The deputy governor pointed out that the school will be a
unique one where teaching staff will be hired from resource
persons with practical experience and not full-time staff.
</P>
<P>
The school is expected to be self-sustaining in three years
and no donor funds will be used on the institution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 0830 GMT, February 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING -- A solemn memorial meeting attended by 10,000 people
was held today at the Great Hall of the People for Comrade Deng
Xiaoping, who passed away last Wednesday at the age of 93.
</P>
<P>
Among those invited to the service, which was telecast live for
both domestic and overseas audiences, were members of the Funeral
Committee or the representatives for some members who were away
from Beijing, representatives of the Party and government
institutions, army headquarters, people's organizations, and
people from all walks of life in the Chinese capital, Deng's
friends and representatives from his hometown.
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- Apologizing for a major loan scandal, South Korean
President Kim Young-sam said today that he will bar one of his
sons from social activities for his alleged involvement.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a televised address on the fourth anniversary of
his inauguration, Kim said that "I, as the president, offer a
sincere apology to the people" over the scandal swirling around
the failed Hanbo Steel Company.
</P>
<P>
Hanbo Steel, the flagship of the Hanbo Group, went bankrupt on
January 23 after racking up 5.8 billion U.S. dollars in debt. The
debt was incurred mostly in government-controlled bank loans,
which Hanbo secured after giving bribes.
</P>
<P>
"What troubles me more is that the name of one of my sons is
talked about in connection with this case," Kim said in his
address. 
</P>
</TEXT>
