<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine House Suspends Hearings on Charter Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine House of
Representatives has decided to suspend any scheduled public
hearings on the move to amend the country's 1987 constitution.
</P>
<P>
Pedro Romualdo, chairman of the House Committee on
Constitutional Amendments, said today that it is useless to go on
with any move to amend the charter due to strong opposition from
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
He said the Senate has already signified its firm opposition to
any charter change in a resolution signed by 20 senators.
</P>
<P>
Once the Senate changes its stand, he added, the committee will
reconvene to continue with its pending tasks.
</P>
<P>
The committee was supposed to act on a House resolution for
convening both chambers of the congress into a constituent
assembly as a prelude to a "people's initiative" to amend the
constitution to extend the term limits and the election of
senators by region.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, 67 congressmen who are second termers
 expressed their opposition to any charter change.
</P>
<P>
The second termers said that if the 89 third termer congressmen
are to run again, they will have no chance to sit as committee
chairmen.
</P>
<P>
At the House, seniority is the basis of getting a committee's
chairmanship.  
</P>
</TEXT>
