<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar's Slide Eases Pressure on Thai Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Pressure on the baht, the Thai
currency, has eased as the U.S. dollar lost some ground against
the Japanese yen and the German mark.
</P>
<P>
The ease has led to a slight strengthening of the baht, which
has been depreciating against the rising dollar for months.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand set the mid-rate of the baht at 25.94 to
the dollar on Monday, down 4 satangs from the last trading day,
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Trade was light in the spot market, with the baht moving in a
wide range from 25.87 to 25.96 baht against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Analysts forecast that the dollar would move downward to about
121 yen, compared with the 124.49 level it reached last week.
</P>
<P>
Siri Garnjarerndee, assistant governor of the central bank,
said that the foreign exchange and money markets were moving
closer to a normal position and that the baht and the dollar were
traded in a wider range, providing investors with more strategies
and thereby easing pressure.
</P>
<P>
Less volatile trading brought the forward swap premium down to
11-12 satangs for one-month settlement, 62-63.5 satangs for six
months and 106-110 for one year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
