<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fungal Disease Threatens Maize Yield in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe might fail to produce
its estimated maize yield of about three million tons this
season, following the recent outbreak of the fungal grey leaf
spot disease in its commercial and some communal farming areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily "The Herald" today, the disease, also
known as corcospora zeae-maydis, wreaks havoc on the maize crop
only and can destroy enormous hectares within a season.
</P>
<P>
Being a fungal disease, it also has the capacity to move with
the wind over great distances.
</P>
<P>
Maize production was this season expected to increase from 2.6
million tons to about three million tons, but unless measures
are taken to curb the spread of the disease, the yields would,
without doubt, be reduced, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Its outbreak was first reported in the United States in 1925
and spread to the African continent in 1988, where it settled in
South Africa and some central African countries.
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, the grey spot disease is said to have moved
up to 400 km, destroying vast maize fields in one season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
