<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's New Foreign Exchange Payment Rules to Take Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 25 (Xinhua) -- New regulations to verify
foreign exchange payments for imports will be put into effect on
March 1 by the State Administration of Foreign Exchange, today's
China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The new rules place direct responsibility on the administration
for conducting verifications of the import payments.
</P>
<P>
The administration will take over the task from banks which
lack the management tools to make the verifications efficiently.
</P>
<P>
China has adopted the verification system to ensure the
authenticity of import procedures and to prevent illegal
remittances of foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a foreign exchange official as saying that
"it is even more necessary to set up a simple and effective
verification-monitoring system now that the yuan is convertible
under current accounts."
</P>
<P>
The new regulations will standardize import payment activities
and prevent confusion between current and capital accounts
activities.
</P>
<P>
Designed banks are to report foreign exchange payment
statistics to the administration; importers are to report
certification and information concerning the arrival of imported
goods.
</P>
<P>
The administration then will check the importers' reports
against information received from banks and customs
bureaux. Further, some importers will be subject to random
inspections, according to the new regulations.
</P>
<P>
Firms found in violation of the regulations will be fined and
placed on a special list.
</P>
<P>
Firms on the inspection list will be permitted to do import
payment activities only after the administration confirm the
authenticity of their exports.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange administration will also discuss a list of
trade organizations and foreign-funded ventures which can directly
conduct import payment activities with designated banks.
</P>
<P>
The issuing of the two lists is to convince importers to
operate legally and so keep their reputations intact.
</P>
<P>
"Gaining the right to conduct foreign exchange payments
directly with banks will reflect a firm's credibility," said the
official, adding that the administration will adjust the two lists
periodically.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations will also make it convenient for importers
to report information to do import payment.
</P>
<P>
Periodic reports will be required, rather than reporting and
verifying each import transaction, as required at present.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0153 </DOCNO>
