<HEADLINE> India Seeks U.S. Missile Technology From Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 25 (Xinhua) -- India is negotiating with
Israel to acquire U.S. missile technology even as Washington
increases pressure to prevent the country from building an arsenal
of missiles.
</P>
<P>
Indian Defense Secretary T. Banerjee was in Israel a fortnight
ago at the head of an Army and Air Force team to negotiate the
purchase of components and technology of the Israeli "Arrow"
missile program, a joint venture with the United States, Defense
Ministry sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
India needs advanced launching and guidance systems to perfect
its surface-to-surface missile "Prithvi," which has a range of 250
kilometers, and the fledgling submarine-launched missile
"Sagvarika."
</P>
<P>
Last year India's Defense Research and Development Organization
chief A. P. J. Abdul Kalam visited Israel to study that country's
expertise in missile and related technologies.
</P>
<P>
Israel is negotiating the sale of a number of defense systems
worth 500 million U.S. dollars with India, including a large
contract for the supply of electronic systems for the upgrading of
Mig-21 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Indo-Israeli defense ties are expected to grow following the
visit of Israeli President Ezer Weizman to India a couple of
months ago when the two countries signed an agreement on
cooperation in the defense industry. No details have been given
about the agreement, but reports said it would translate into
India sourcing Western components from Israel at a low cost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
