<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Tightens Controls on Weapons Possession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 25 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
decided to tighten controls on the possession of offensive weapons
 and will use the full force of emergency regulations including
the death penalty and the forfeiture of property, Defense Ministry
sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The sources explained that offensive weapons include bombs,
grenades and other devices capable of causing injury to persons or
damage to property.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry has also sought the cooperation of the
public for the recovery of unauthorized guns and explosives.
Substantial rewards have been promised for information that would
lead to the recovery of weapons, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
They added that the new stand of the government is a result of
the grave situation that has risen in the country, where guns and
other weapons, explosives and ammunition are being held by persons
without authorization.
</P>
<P>
Local government elections have been scheduled for March 21 and
police said that since the handing in of nominations on February
12 more than 350 incidents of violence have been reported in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
