<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Develops AIDS Test Kit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 25 (Xinhua) --India has developed a new kit
for detecting AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
A team of micro-biologists at the All India Institute of
Medical Sciences (AIIMS) in New Delhi, capital of India, developed
the kit to detect the deadly human immune-deficiency virus (HIV),
causative agent of AIDS, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Pradeep Seth, head of the Department of Micro-Biology and
his research associate Dr. Mohammed Najeeb Siddiqi developed the
kit after two years' hard work.
</P>
<P>
A key feature of this enzyme linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA)
kit is its high sensitivity to the AIDS virus. "It has 100 percent
sensitive and specificity. We did tests on more than 1,000 blood
samples which were available in our bank, and we did not miss a
single one. More than 500 random samples were alone done. There
were no errors in detecting HIV positive cases here as well," Dr.
Seth said.
</P>
<P>
A major drawback with several kits available in India has been
the high degree of error. Recently several such kits had to be
withdrawn from the market due to the high error percentage.
</P>
<P>
"The sensitivity of a HIV testing kit is crucial. If a HIV
positive case is declared as negative, the person can die
prematurely due to lack of treatment. Similarly, if a negative
case is declared as positive, it can be traumatic for the person,"
Dr. Seth further said.
</P>
<P>
The kit is specifically sensitive to HIV types prevalent in
India.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
