<HEADLINE> Taliban Claim Seizure of Strategic Shibar Pass </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 25 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
have claimed the seizure of the strategic pass which is the
gateway to a rival faction's stronghold north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban forces Monday night broke through two defense lines
of the anti-Taliban alliance and captured the Shibar Pass, local
newspapers reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The Shibar Pass opens out to Bamyan Province, the stronghold of
the Shiite Hezb-e-Wahdat faction led by Karim Khalili and provides
access to Baghlan and Samangan provinces in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
If the report is true, the loss of the Shibar Pass represents a
major setback for the anti-Taliban alliance which comprises forces
of Khalili, northern warlord Rashid Dostum and ex-defense minister
Ahmad Masood.
</P>
<P>
Together with the Salang Pass which was blocked when Dostum's
retreating troops blew up the road near the Salang Tunnel in the
Hindu Kush Mountains, the Shibar Pass is the doorway to the 10
provinces in northern Afghanistan controlled by the anti-Taliban
alliance.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, which control two-thirds of Afghanistan, have
vowed to bring the whole country under their control and enforce a
true Islamic system there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
