<HEADLINE> NZ Prime Minister Mourns Death of Deng Xiaoping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 25 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jim Bolger paid a visit to the Chinese Embassy here today to
express his condolences on the death of Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
He signed the condolence book and watched briefly the live
telecast of the memorial rally for Deng Xiaoping being held in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Bolger sent a message of condolence to Chinese
Premier Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
He said in the message that "with the passing of Deng Xiaoping,
 China has lost a distinguished citizen and leader renowned
throughout the world as the architect of the successful economic
reform and opening policies that, since 1978, have placed China
firmly on the road to national prosperity and full participation
in the international community."
</P>
<P>
"During his long life of service to the cause of the
rejuvenation of the Chinese nation, Deng Xiaoping directed his
efforts above all to improving the living standards of the Chinese
people. Through his policies, he has left behind a legacy of the
fastest and deepest improvement in living standards, affecting the
greatest number of people, in the history of the world. This is
Deng Xiaoping's legacy not only to the Chinese people, but to the
people of the world as a whole."
</P>
<P>
"New Zealanders share in the loss of such a leader of this
century," Bolger said.  
</P>
