<HEADLINE> Nepali Ruling MPs Demand Smaller Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 25 (Xinhua) -- A dozen of Nepal's ruling
MPs demanded that Prime Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba should trim
his cabinet, the local press said today.
</P>
<P>
12 MPs of Deuba's main ruling Nepali Congress (NC) party Monday
urged him to reduce his 47-member cabinet before the winter
session of parliament scheduled from March 3, the Kathmandu Post
quoted sources close to the prime minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
The NC lawmakers, who earlier registered their letters saying
they would not be present at the parliament session, promised
their support to the coalition government during the session if
Deuba reshuffles the cabinet before it begins, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Deuba is expected to seek a vote of confidence
for his three-party government during the parliament session under
pressure from the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Any ruling MPs' absence from the session is considered
disastrous for the fate of Deuba's government, which had been
reduce into minority status by a no-confidence challenge of the
main opposition Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist,
CPN-UML) in last December.
</P>
<P>
The main ruling NC party, which leads the coalition government,
earlier this month directed Deuba to trim his cabinet after the
prime minister expanded the cabinet to induct some MPs of the
ruling partners in an attempt to stabilize the shaky ruling
coalition.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, five ministers from the NC party have reportedly
offered to resign to make it easy for the prime minister to
reshuffle the cabinet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
