<HEADLINE> Container Truck Explosion Might be Caused by Fuel in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 25 (Xinhua) -- The explosion on Tuesday
afternoon of a container truck could be caused by the fuel in the
second-hand motorcycles being transported by the vehicle,
according to local press reports here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We believe (the explosion) might have been caused by
inflammable liquid in the motorcycles inside the container," said
Yeung Kwong-hung, Divisional Fire Services Commander Kowloon East.
</P>
<P>
"Somehow it burned and led to the explosion," he added.
</P>
<P>
Three people were injured in the explosion of the packed truck
at a busy Wong Tai Sin highway but the 36-year-old truck driver
escaped unhurt just before the main of a series of blasts.
</P>
<P>
The injured were two drivers and a two-year-old girl in a
nearby flat and they were all treated and discharged.
</P>
<P>
The blast at about 5:40 PM on Lung Cheung Road sent burning
motorcycle debris as far as 120 meters away. They scattered a
large area in a sea of smoke and flames.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 firemen rushed to the site and the fire was put out in
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of Hong Kong's Transport Department said Monday
night that the current legislation did not cover fuel in goods
carried by lorries and other commercial vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Transport Advisory Committee chairman Raymond Ho Chung-tai said
safety aspects of long vehicles transporting other vehicles must
be looked into in a small city with heavy traffic like Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
