<HEADLINE> Turkmenistan President Visiting India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW Delhi, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Turkmenistan President S.A.
Niyazov is arriving here today on a two-day state visit to India
for enhancing bilateral ties with India, especially in the fields
of economy and trade, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
India and Turkmenistan are expected to sign a cooperation
agreement on oil and natural gas during the visit.
</P>
<P>
"Turkmenistan represents a major market for our goods and a
major source of energy for us," said Ministry of External Affairs
Secretary K. Raghunath.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan president's visit comes on the heels of a
trilateral agreement signed last weekend in Teheran by Indian
External Affairs Minister I.K. Gujral and his Iranian and
Turkmenistan counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The trade and transit agreement laid down the framework for
regulating and monitoring the movement of goods between India and
Turkmenistan, a major gateway to central Asia.
</P>
<P>
The trilateral agreement, which had been in the making for the
past two years, will allow normalization and facilitation of
various procedures for the transport and transit of goods.
Furthermore, with a reliable rail link recently established from
Iran's Bandar Abbas port, and the excellent Soviet-era roads
leading from Ashkabad to central Asia, and onward to China in one
direction and Europe in the other, India expects its trade with
the region to receive a big boost in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
India is deeply interested in cooperating with Turkmenistan in
the area of hydrocarbons, since the Caspian sea basin is rich in
oil and natural gas, Raghunath said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
