<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Calls on U.S. to Suspend Mass Deportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- A decision by the United
States to deport 20,000 Nicaraguans within the next few days could
create serious problems for Nicaragua as the deportees arrive home
to face unemployment and homelessness, the Nicaraguan Foreign
Ministry said here today.
</P>
<P>
The mass deportation could bring about grave consequences to
Nicaragua's impoverished economy as the government struggles to
create new jobs, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua is one of the poorest countries in Latin America with
52 percent of its workforce unemployed or underemployed.
</P>
<P>
In 1970s and 1980s, about 25 percent of Nicaragua's population
sought political asylum abroad, while 200,000 took up residence in
Miami, U.S.A..
</P>
<P>
However, the exiles can no longer claim they face political
persecution back home to avoid deportation now because of the
democratic elections in Nicaragua in 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Tough immigration laws signed by U.S. President Bill Clinton
last year required all American-based Nicaraguans who had received
deportation letters to leave.
</P>
<P>
So far, about 20,000 Nicaraguans in Florida are facing
deportation in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
Playing down the danger of the mass deportation, Nicaraguan
President Arnoldo Aleman said on Sunday that his government will
ask the U.S. government to give Nicaraguans in the
U.S. provisional status until Nicaragua is able to meet their
social needs after they come back.
</P>
<P>
"I do not believe that the situation is as alarming as the
media has reported," Aleman said.
</P>
<P>
Aleman, who took power on January 10, has said he would join
with presidents of other Central American countries, asking
Clinton to temporarily suspend the deportation of Central American
illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
The issue of deportation will be one of the major topics up for
discussion between Clinton and Central American leaders during the
U.S. president's visit to the region in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
