<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Leader Stresses Consolidation of National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Senior-General
Than Shwe has stressed the need to consolidate national solidarity
in building the nation.
</P>
<P>
Than Shwe, chairman of Myanmar State Law and Order Restoration
Council (SLORC), made the remark in a speech to the students of
the University for Development of National Races here on Monday,
official paper The New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
"With the reduction in the number of armed conflicts, work can
be done extensively in political, economic and social tasks," he
said, noting that there has been improvement in general conditions
in the country accordingly.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that there remains only one armed group at
present, which is believed to be the Kayin National Union (KNU).
</P>
<P>
"The rest are implementing nation-building projects in
cooperation with the government," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The government is carrying out its tasks with the belief that
opposing groups above-ground would be reunited one day," he added.
</P>
<P>
He declared that it would not be enough to deter those inside
and outside the country who turned out to be destructive elements,
warning that they would have to be crushed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, vice-chairman of Myanmar SLORC General Maung Aye,
during an inspection tour on Monday to the country's Kayin state,
accused the KNU of unilaterally suspending the negotiations with
the government which had been held for four times.
</P>
<P>
Over 500 KNU members surrendered to the government following a
mopping-up operation by government troops in the middle of this
month in Kayin state.  
</P>
</TEXT>
