<HEADLINE> Hundreds in Russia Mourn Deng's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Peoples from all
walks of life in Russia went to the Chinese Embassy here today to
express their condolences over the death of Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
Nikolai Kovalev, director of the Federal Security Service, paid
tribute to Deng with a flower presentation, hailing the late
Chinese leader as the greatest reformer in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
Viktor Somsonov, first deputy defense minister, wrote in the
memorial book that the Russian military would always think of Deng
as the greatest son, state and military activist of China.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Communist Party chief, Gennady Zyuganov, told
reporters at the embassy that it was the reforms initiated by Deng
that resulted in the present significant achievements in China.
</P>
<P>
He believed the Chinese people would continue to march
triumphantly along the socialist road.
</P>
<P>
Guo Liancheng, an old Chinese living in Russia for more than 30
years, said with tears in his eyes, that without Deng Xiaoping,
there would be no today's China.
</P>
<P>
The old man added that all overseas Chinese were proud of
Deng's fruitful reforms because that helped them live with dignity
outside China.
</P>
<P>
Deng died late Wednesday, aged 93. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
