<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Posts Budget Deficit in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
posted a budget deficit of 3.4 billion pesos (130 million US
dollars) in January due to big revenue shortfalls registered by
its three revenue collection agencies.
</P>
<P>
Official sources also attributed the deficit to low
privatization receipts during the period, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau of Treasury documents showed that total revenues
last month reached only 37.26 billion pesos (1.43 billion US
dollars), while expenditures reached 40.65 billion pesos (1.56
billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
All the three collection agencies, the Bureau of Internal
Revenue, the Bureau of Customs and the Treasury, posted shortfalls
totaling 6 billion pesos (228 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The documents showed that tax revenues accounted for the bulk
of the government's revenues at 34.73 billion pesos (1.33 billion
US dollars). Non-tax revenues totaled 2.38 billion pesos (91.54
million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Last month's budget deficit showed a reversal from the 220
million pesos (8.5 million US dollars) surplus registered in the
same month last year.
</P>
<P>
The government has scaled down its 1997 budget surplus target
to 12.14 billion pesos (467 million US dollars) from an initial
target of 14.7 billion pesos (565 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government has posted budget surpluses in the past two
years-- 6.26 billion pesos (241 million US dollars) in 1996, and
11.07 billion pesos (426 million US dollars) in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
