<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Trade Unions Help Workers in Distress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Trade unions at all levels in
east China's Zhejiang Province extend a helping hand to laid-off
and poverty-stricken workers.
</P>
<P>
In the year 1996 the province's trade unions allocated a relief
fund of about 20 million yuan (about 2.5 million US dollars) for
poverty-stricken workers and established files to keep in touch
with more than 20,000 workers living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
A system has been established in 13 cities and counties across
the province to grant preferential treatment to 2,342 poor workers.
</P>
<P>
As many as 320 separate funds have been established, with the
total money available amounting to 38 million yuan. Meanwhile,
nearly 20,000 unemployed workers have found new jobs with help
from the trade unions.
</P>
<P>
Various kinds of insurance funds have also been established in
Zhejiang to cover wider aspects of workers' lives.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
