<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Reports Trade Surplus in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Chile reported a trade
surplus of 23 million U.S. dollars for January, in spite of a near
doubling of petrol imports, the Central Bank said today.
</P>
<P>
Exports were up 16 percent over January 1995 to 1.474 billion
dollars, while imports rose 6 percent to 1.45 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bank said petroleum imports increased by 96 percent
compared with January 1995 and blamed the rise on the country's
drought, which had led to an increased use of oil as a fuel
substitute.
</P>
<P>
Overseas copper sales increased 27 percent but the price of
copper dropped 7 percent while non-traditional exports increased
25 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
