<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last Surviving Signatory of U.N. Charter Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Guatemala's Guillermo Torriello
Garrido, the last surviving signatory of the San Francisco
Charter, the founding document of the United Nations (U.N.), died
today in Havana at the age of 85.
</P>
<P>
Torriello was Guatemala's foreign minister during the
governments of Juan Jose Arevalo in 1945 and Jacobo Arbenz in
1954. He had a crowded record of service in favor of just causes,
both in his country and in the international sphere.
</P>
<P>
The United States intervention in his homeland caused Torriello
to live in exile.
</P>
<P>
After living in Europe and Mexico, Torriello moved to Costa
Rica in 1979 to join the Sandinista National Liberation Front, and
participated, at the age of 68, in the liberation of Managua.
</P>
<P>
The former Guatemalan foreign minister was living in Cuba where
he dedicated his energies to the unity of Latin America and to
activities against what he described as U.S. expansionism.
</P>
<P>
Before his death, Torriello was the president of the
Association for the Unity of Our America, which is based in Havana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
