<HEADLINE> US Secretary of State Leaves Beijing for Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright left here this morning for home after
concluding her 20-hour visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who arrived in Beijing Monday, was the first member
of the new Clinton administration to visit China, which was
the last leg of her nine-country, 11-day global trip, the first
since becoming US Secretary of State.
</P>
<P>
During his meetings with Chinese leaders, Albright expressed
the condolences of US President Bill Clinton and the American
people over the passing away of Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
During her stay in Beijing, she was received by Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng and held talks with
Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen.
</P>
<P>
In the meetings and talks, Albright exchanged views with the
Chinese leaders on a broad range of issues concerning Sino-US
relations and major regional and international issues.
</P>
<P>
She also discussed with Qian Qichen on other issues of common
interests including China's accession to the World Trade
Organization, non-proliferation of weapons, and the Hong Kong
issue.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident, based on these meetings, that the vigorous
strategic dialogue that is developing between the United States
and China will continue." she told a news conference Monday night.
</P>
<P>
"My visit here reaffirmed America's commitment to strategic
dialogue that is developing between the United States and China
will continue." she told the conference.  
</P>
