<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USDA Forecasts Slower Growth in Food Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Agriculture Department
has forecasted that food prices would moderate this year after
rising at the fastest rate in six years in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The forecast, released today at USDA's annual Agricultural
Outlook Forum, shows the cost of food consumed at home would rise
by 1.8 percent this year, much slower than the 3.7 percent gain in
1996.
</P>
<P>
It said that food prices in the country are expected to rise
just by 2.1 percent this year, down sharply from 3.3 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
The forecast said that meat costs would increase only by 1.1
percent this year, down from the 3.5 percent advance in 1996. Pork
is expected to post a 1.2 percent advance comparing with the 9.9
percent gain in 1996. The price of poultry is projected to fall by
0.9 percent after jumping 6.2 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The rise of food prices in the U.S. last year was the steepest
since prices increased by 5.8 percent in 1990 when the economy was
entering the recession.
</P>
<P>
USDA economist Annette Clauson said much of the overall food
price increase in 1996 was due to higher grain prices that
affected the retail cost of meat, poultry and eggs, diary products
and cereal products.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Price Index in the U.S. for all goods and services
rose by 3 percent in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Province's Rural Economy Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, February 25 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Henan
Province has reported all-round development in its rural economy
since the beginning of the Ninth Five-Year-Plan (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, the province is expected to add
94.8 billion yuan in profits from developments in agriculture,
forestry, animal husbandry, and fisheries in 1996, a rise of 11.2
percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Henan is one of China's leading agricultural provinces. In
recent years, provincial officials have placed strengthening the
agricultural foundation at the top of their economic development
list and have managed to put more investment into the sector to
increase farmers' initiative in production.
</P>
<P>
Their efforts have had some effect. Last year, the province had
marked increases in the area devoted to grain, in meat output, and
in rural industry.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers have also benefited greatly. Per capita net
income of farmers in the province was 1,530 yuan in 1996, a rise
of 11 percent over the previous year when adjusted for inflation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Federal Deficit Up 27 Percent in First 4 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. federal government
recorded a budget surplus in January for the second consecutive
month, but the deficit for first four months of fiscal 1997 was
larger than the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Treasury Department said today that budget surplus in
January totaled 13.4 billion dollars, pulling down the deficit in
the first four months of fiscal 1997 to 46 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Still, the deficit was 27 percent higher than the red ink
recorded during the first four months of fiscal year of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The full-year deficit of 107 billion dollars in fiscal 1996 was
the lowest in 17 years. The Clinton administration is projecting
the deficit will increase to 125.6 billion by the end of fiscal
1997 ending on September 30.
</P>
<P>
The department noted that the 1996 deficit in today's report
was slightly lower than the 107.3 billion previously recorded,
primarily because of a shift in the reported timing of spending by
the Federal Housing Administration.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. federal deficit hit a record high of 290.4 billion
dollars in fiscal 1992 and then dropped in each of the following
years since President Bill Clinton took office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
