<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Cancer Increase Links Nuclear Power Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Radiation released in an
accident at Pennsylvania's Three Mile Island nuclear power plant
may have increased cancer rates in the area, showed a study
published today.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at the University of North Carolina applied new
analytical techniques to old data and found stronger evidence that
the partial meltdown at Three Mile Island increased cancer risks
for residents living within 10 miles of the plant outside
Harrisburg, Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
A 1990 study, performed at Columbia University, said the 1979
accident was not responsible for slightly increased cancer rates
near the area because the radiation released was low. But the new
study said radiation doses may have been higher than originally
thought.
</P>
<P>
It said lung cancer and leukaemia rates downwind of the reactor
were 2 to 10 times higher than upwind rates.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a U.S. District Court in Harrisburg dismissed 2,000
damage claims against the power plant, saying area residents
failed to provide enough evidence the accident may have made them
ill. The ruling is being appealed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Memorial Services for Deng Xiaoping Held in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 24 (Xinhua) -- People from various circles
in the eastern areas of the United States staged various kinds of
memorial service to express their deep sorrow and painful sadness
on the passing away of Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
Chinese living in New York city held today a memorial meeting
in China Town, which was joined by Chinese diplomatic officials
here.
</P>
<P>
Huang Qicheng, president of the United Chinese Associations of
New York, said at the meeting that Deng's idea of reunification of
the country has deeply rooted among the overseas Chinese. He will
be remembered forever.
</P>
<P>
Over the past week, more than 2,000 Chinese, originated from
both the Chinese mainland and Taiwan, foreign diplomats and
Chinese students attended the mourning ceremonies held in the
Chinese Consulate General and China's Permanent Mission to the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Kofi Annan, Secretary-General of the United Nations, was one of
the first few U.N. officials going to the Chinese mission to
express their condolences. He described Deng's death as "a great
loss, not only for the people of China but for the whole world."
</P>
<P>
Razali Ismail, the president of the 51th United Nations who
also appeared at the Chinese mission's mourning hall, said Deng
contributed "immensely to the elevation of China and to the
aspirations of people of the world."
</P>
<P>
Bill Richardson, the U.S. new ambassador to the United Nations,
also went to the Chinese mission to express his condolence. He
wrote that "My most sincere condolence for a leader who greatly
improved U.S.-China relations and greatly modernize China's
economic system. He was a great leader who will be missed on the
world stage."
</P>
<P>
At the weekend, some Chinese drove hours from upper part of the
New York state, Philadelphia and New Jersey to express their sorrow
at the mourning hall of the Chinese Consulate General. The
wreathes in the hall also included those presented by the
governments of nearby cities, such as Jersey City and Mount Vernon.
</P>
<P>
I. M. Pei, the famous American Chinese architect, told the
reporter he personally held that Deng's greatest contribution to
the nation was his introduction of market economy which had
immensely improved people's livelihood.
</P>
<P>
Chinese from some organizations of Taiwan also joined the
mourning of their compatriots. Some of them, working as
interpreters for the U.N., recalled their witness of Deng's first
explanation of China's theory of three worlds during a U.N.
session in 1974. They described Deng Xiaoping as a great man who
made great contribution to the people.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Chinese Consulate General, who were also in
deep mourning, said they were really moved by some of the
mourners, one of whom brought a wreath made by 93 fresh roses.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese student named Tu said that without Deng's initiation
of the opening up policy, it would be hardly possible for large
numbers of students to study abroad. They have not only gained
advanced knowledge, but also contributed to the motherland in
various forms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
