<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Economic Zone Reporting Faster Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, February 25 (Xinhua) -- The city of Xiamen, one of
China's first special economic zones, in east China's Fujian
Province, had a GDP of 30.82 billion yuan last year, a rise of
19.25 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The latter figure is 10 percentage points more than the
nation's average, but the city held down price hikes and the
retail price index compared with the national average, said local
officials.
</P>
<P>
Local industrial enterprises at or above the township level
generated 39.59 billion yuan in output value and contributed 4.23
billion yuan in revenues.
</P>
<P>
Local officials consider overseas-backed businesses as a major
force behind the fast economic growth of the special economic
zone. In 1996, those at or above the township level generated 30.1
billion yuan in output value, accounting for 76.1 percent of the
city's total industrial output value from industrial enterprises
at and above township level.  
</P>
</TEXT>
