<HEADLINE> European Shares Mixed, Frankfurt, Paris Slightly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
traded flat and ended mixed Monday, with Frankfurt and Paris
slightly higher while London marginally down, as Wall Street's
rally did little to help the markets.
</P>
<P>
British shares in London regained some early losses later in
the day to end the session off the day's lows, helped by a revival
of the Dow, but still in the negative ground, with the FTSE 100
index 5.7 points lower at 4,331.1.
</P>
<P>
Traders said a weaker dollar and rising bond yields, together
with concern that the US Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's
semi-annual commentary on the US economy to Senate and House
committees on Wednesday and Thursday might unsettle markets,
undermined share prices.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares recovered their earlier losses and
ended marginally higher, with the DAX-30 index 0.12 points up at
3,184.21.
</P>
<P>
There was little positive sentiment in the market which was
depressed by a weak dollar which is negative for German exports,
dealers said.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, share prices bucked the weaker
international trend on strength in selected stocks and fresh
buying at the start of the March trading account, with the CAC-40
index ending 5.01 points higher at 2,567.85.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index of leading British shares ended 5.7
points lower at 4,331.1. The Frankfurt DAX-30 index finished 0.12
points up at 3,184.21. In Paris, the CAC-40 index closed up 5.01
points at 2,567.85.  
</P>
</TEXT>
