<HEADLINE> Britain Set to Table New Proposals on Lifting Beef Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The British government is
poised to present a package of proposals aimed at a partial
lifting of the European Union's (EU) global ban on British beef
exports to the EU Commission.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for British Agriculture Ministry was quoted by BBC
television as saying this evening that it was "more than likely"
that the plans would be put forward to an EU veterinary committee
on Tuesday and then the agriculture ministers of the 15-nation
bloc.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that the new certified herd scheme was
designed to ensure that exports come only from cattle which have
never been in contact with BSE or mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Northern Ireland are likely among the first wave
to benefit from the partial lifting of the beef ban as there are
better records of cows' history in the region.
</P>
<P>
The EU imposed a world-wide ban on exports of British beef
products last March when the British government acknowledged
possible links between mad cow disease to its human equivalent
Creutzfeldt Jakob Disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
