<HEADLINE> IDB Increases Its Borrowings Largely in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) increased its borrowings in the world
capital market last year, strengthening its ability in aiding
development projects in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
A IDB report released today said that the bank completed 20
individual borrowings in the international capital market in 1996,
totaling 4.25 billion U.S. dollars. It was an increase of 1.5
billion dollars comparing with 1995.
</P>
<P>
The IDB expects to borrow between 4 billion and 5 billion U.S.
dollars in 1997 with 100 percent of the swap requirements in U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
During the next few years, the bank's annual borrowing
requirements are expected to remain close to or slightly above the
1996 level, the report said.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year, the bank's outstanding borrowings
reached 26.6 billion U.S. dollars with an average life of six
years.
</P>
<P>
The borrowing program of IDB raises financial resources for the
economic and social development of Latin America and Caribbean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
