<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: U.S. Spend More on Prisons Than Colleges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
spending more money on building prisons than building
universities, a report of The Washington Post said today.
</P>
<P>
"From 1987 to 1995, state government expenditures on prisons
increased by 30 percent while spending on higher education fell by
18 percent," said the Post, quoting a study which was conducted by
the Justice Policy Institute, a research and advocacy organization
based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
It said that many states are rapidly expanding prison
facilities while the size of their college-age population has
remained static for several years.
</P>
<P>
The study found that in 1995, spending by states on prison
construction increased by 926 million U.S. dollars, but building
funds for higher education decreased by an almost equal amount.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department said, from 1980 to 1994, the number of
adults in prison nationwide tripled from 320,000 to 992,000 as
lawmakers across the country enacted longer sentences for many
crimes, including nonviolent drug offenses.
</P>
<P>
However, over the same period, enrollment in institutions of
higher education increased from 12 million to 14.7 million people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
