<HEADLINE> UN Calls upon Afghanistan's Taleban to Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations on
Monday called upon the Islamic Taleban to release two French aid
workers.
</P>
<P>
Two Frenchman from the Paris-based group Action Against Hunger
were arrested over the weekend by Taleban militia for, as the
Taleban's information minister put it, "tramping under foot
Islamic and international moral principles.
</P>
<P>
"We are making four points to the Taleban," U.N. spokesman Fred
Eckhard said. Among them was that private or non-governmental
humanitarian groups, which supply considerable aid, would be
"inclined to leave Afghanistan if the two are not released."
</P>
<P>
The Taleban was also told that its actions were a violation of
diplomatic norms and that the Frenchmen should be released on
humanitarian grounds because they committed no offense to justify
their arrest, he said.
</P>
<P>
It was also told that "unless these two people are released the
Taleban's international image would be further undermined," he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
