<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Stresses Equitable Use of Nile Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia is "prepared to
sit and engage in fruitful discussion with other Nile riparians
in the determination of their equitable shares of water," a
senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
But this should be "based on progressively developed and
universally acceptable principles of international law
particularly within the sub-basin countries of the Blue Nile,"
Ethiopian Minister of Water Resources Shiferaw Tarso said here.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by Tarso when he was opening the 5th
Nile 2002 Conference at the United Nations Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
The minister said: "as a source and major contribution of the
Nile waters, Ethiopia has the right to have an equitable share of
the Nile waters and reserves its right to make use of its water."
</P>
<P>
However, Tarso said: "In the exercise of its sovereign right
to the utilization of its waters, Ethiopia has no intention to
cause appreciable or significant harm to other riparian states."
</P>
<P>
He called on participants to "create a viable framework for
effective cooperation in all areas of endeavor, ranging from
integrated basin development, effective utilization of their
resources as well as the sustainable development and protection
of its environment."
</P>
<P>
On behalf of 17 financial supporters to the conference,
Canadian Ambassador to Ethiopia Gabriel Lessord said: "Canada has
been assisting the Nile Basin countries toward achieving the goal
of comprehensive management of the water resources of the Nile
Basin."
</P>
<P>
"We also very much desire that once success has been achieved
on working together on the uses of water resources, and that
confidence is created between the member states, that other
pressing strategic issues can also be addressed," he added.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the five-day conference is "Comprehensive Water
Resources Development of the Nile Basin: Basis for Cooperation".
</P>
<P>
Over 300 participants will discuss issues and topics that will
foster regional cooperation in the basin under the focal theme,
basis for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The conference is held annually in each of the 10 countries on
rotational basis. Four conferences were held in Aswan, Egypt in
February 1993, Khartoum, Sudan in January 1994, Arusha, Tanzania
in February 1995 and Kampala, Uganda in February 1996
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The 6,600-km River Nile is one of the longest and most
remarkable rivers in the world. The Nile Basin area is estimated
to be about 3 million square km, the equivalent of about
one-tenth of the African continent, extending into 10 riparian
countries, namely Burundi, Rwanda, Zaire, Tanzania, Kenya,
Uganda, Ethiopia, Eritrea, Sudan and Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
