<HEADLINE> More HK People Mourn Death of Deng Xiaoping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 24 (Xinhua) -- More people in Hong Kong
went to the mourning hall at the Xinhua New Agency Hong Kong
Branch here today for the fifth day to offer their condolences
over the death of Deng Xiaoping who passed away last Wednesday at
the age of 93.
</P>
<P>
A winding queue of waiting mourners was seen throughout today,
the last day of mourning at the hall.
</P>
<P>
Among them were business people, students, teachers, workers,
Buddhists, entertainers, tourists from the Chinese mainland and
diplomatic envoys in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Postcards on Hong Kong's landscapes, a guidebook of Hong Kong
and a calendar of 1997 were laid before Deng's portrait, to let
him "have a look at Hong Kong" after it returns to its motherland,
mourners said.
</P>
<P>
"I miss Grandpa Deng. Thanks to the concept of 'one country,
two systems" put forward by him, Hong Kong is now very stable and
I can go to school at ease as in the past," a tearful primary
school pupil told reporters.
</P>
<P>
A new football was placed before Deng's portrait by a local
football team, as the late Chinese leader "enjoyed the sport very
much."
</P>
<P>
Since the hall opened last Thursday, a total of 43,000 people
have gone there to offer their condolences.
</P>
<P>
Six other mourning halls, set up by Chinese-funded groups, such
as the Bank of China Group, to share the huge number of mourners,
received some 15,000 people during these days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
