<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Documentary Series on Hong Kong to Be on Air, BBC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- A six-part documentary series
on Hong Kong will be on the air in the immediate run-up to the
handover of Hong Kong to China, it was announced by BBC here
today.
</P>
<P>
As the handover of Hong Kong to China is one of the major world
events this year, apart from the planned six-part series, BBC
World Service will also present lots of programs concerning
Hong Kong and China, it added.
</P>
<P>
launching its New Season Programs, BBC World Service Deputy
Managing Director Caroline Thomson said, "China's resumption of
sovereignty over Hong Kong will be an event rich in historical
significance not just for the 6 million people of the territory
itself but also for Britain, China and the world."
</P>
<P>
Former BBC Beijing correspondent Tim Luard, who is in charge of
the series, said that the purpose of presenting the program is to
"reveal Hong Kong's special place in history by explaining the
territory's almost unbelievable development."
</P>
<P>
The New Season Programs include a new regular women's series,
Everywoman, a new forum for answering listener questions, On Your
Behalf, and a new emphasis on debate, science, youth, and British
feature programs.
</P>
<P>
BBC World Service broadcasts around the world in 45 languages
including English. It has a total global audience of 140 million,
35 million listen in English. 
</P>
</TEXT>
