<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Accused of Trying to Find Foothold in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 24 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi Foreign Ministry
spokesman today accused Iran of trying to find a foothold in
northern Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to INA, the spokesman said the Iranian
government tries to get advantage of chances whenever available
to find a foothold in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
These remarks came after Iranian newspapers reported on February
17 that the Iranian government received "alleged representatives
of Iraqi kurdish factions" to take part in ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
By receiving the "alleged representatives" as guests attending
ceremonies, the Iranian government aims to maintain the
abnormal situation in the north, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He refuted the allegations by Iran that it is making efforts
to help stop in-fighting between the Iraqi Kurds.
</P>
<P>
Iraq previously denounced and condemned such practices, which,
the spokesman said, showed Iran's "insistence on interfering with
Iraq's internal affairs and spreading a state of instability in
the region."
</P>
<P>
The statement called upon Iran to stop and keep away from the
"crooked" ways which deeply harm relations between the two
neighbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
