<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Frigate Project in Danger of Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Arguments among the British,
French and Italian partners over ship designs and capability are
threatening to sink the European joint frigate project.
</P>
<P>
The three countries, which all need high-technology frigates,
have been negotiating over the past nine years to produce a new
generation of frigates, the Financial Times newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
But they are sharply divided on what capabilities to give the
new frigate and at the heart of the dispute is the weapon system
of the ship.
</P>
<P>
Britain wants a highly sophisicated frigate capable of
defending a widely-dispersed convoy alone. France and Italy, under
severe budget pressure, are prepared to settle for a less advanced
ship which would only defend the waters immediately around the
ship.
</P>
<P>
Military experts say that the dispute could eventually break up
the program as Britain was not prepared to settle for the lower
capacity, while France and Italy would also refuse to pay the
price Britain has demanded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 100,000 Mozambicans Appeal for Ban on Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, February 24 (Xinhua) -- One day before the opening of
the fourth International Conference on Mines to be held in
Maputo, 100,000 Mozambicans have signed a written appeal for a
ban on the production and sales of mines in the world.
</P>
<P>
The campaign, initiated in the Mozambican capital in early
February, has so far gained huge support among local residents
who have long been the victims of mines ever since the civil war
started in 1964.
</P>
<P>
Banners and placards urging the ban of mines could be seen
everywhere in the streets of Maputo.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said an estimated two million mines have been
planted in the soil of Mozambique. However, despite the end of
the civil war in 1992, people are still suffering from the mine
explosions daily.
</P>
<P>
So far fewer than 50,000 mines have been removed since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Delegations from Mozambique, South Africa, Angola, Zimbabwe,
Cambodia, etc., are expected at the conference which would be
opened by Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
