<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Government Offers Half Price of Grain to Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 24 (Xinhua) -- India's United Front
government today announced in parliament its decision to offer
half a price of rice and wheat to the poor people in the country.
</P>
<P>
A targeted public distribution system (TPDS) will cover 320
million people below the poverty line in the country. At the
beginning, it was to issue 10 kg of food grains per family per
month at half the normal prices for all families below the poverty
line.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Deve Gowda told the house in a statement that a
total of 18 million tons of rice and wheat was likely to be issued
under the TPDS.
</P>
<P>
Massive food subsidy of 82.82 billion rupees (2.33 billion US
dollars) is expected under the new system, an official said.
</P>
<P>
The government's new move is expected to be widely welcomed by
the poor people in the country. As soon as the government came to
power last year, Gowda made it clear that his administration would
work for the poor.
</P>
<P>
Some economists said, however, that the new policy of the
government has made the fiscal deficit management a herculean task
for the beleaguered finance minister, who is scheduled to table
the new budget to parliament on February 28.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and the International Monetary Fund have
recommended a gradual phasing out of subsidies to reign in the
fiscal deficit and ensure better management of resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
