<HEADLINE> Taliban Claim Recovering Lost Territory North of Kabul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
claimed today it has recovered territory it lost to a rival Shiite
Muslim faction in a strategic valley northwest of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The Shiite Hezb-e-Wahdat faction led by Karim Khalili last
night captured some of the Taliban's positions in the Ghorband
valley but they were retaken by the Islamic militia in a dawn
counter-attack, said reports reaching here this evening.
</P>
<P>
The Khalili's forces had been pushed to the foot of the Shebar
pass, which is the gateway to the Bamyan province, a Taliban
spokesman in Kabul was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The claim could not be independently confirmed yet.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban last week sent reinforcements to the Ghorband
valley, 150 km from Kabul, which links Kabul to northern provinces
controlled by the anti-Taliban alliance.
</P>
<P>
The Ghorband valley also controls access to Khalili's
stronghold of central Bamyan province.
</P>
<P>
Khalili is allied with northern warlord Rashid Dostum and
ex-defense minister Ahmad Masood in an anti-Taliban alliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
