<HEADLINE> SADC Defense Forces Discuss Relief Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Defense forces personnel from
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) today started a
three-day meeting in Harare to draft a common strategy on the
management of natural disasters and relief operations.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the SADC inter-state Defense and Security
Committee comes at a time when the air force of Zimbabwe and the
South African air force had to assist with the evacuation of
flood victims marooned in Zimbabwe and Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the Zambian armed forces were called in to uplift
relief supplies and relocate marooned people when floods hit the
Maamba region in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
A follow-up to last October's meeting of SADC defense chiefs,
the meeting has been tasked to come up with Standing Operating
Procedures (SOP) to cover all aspects of disaster management.
</P>
<P>
The procedures will also include prevention, mitigation,
preparedness, response, recovery and disaster related
development.
</P>
<P>
Opening the meeting, Zimbabwe National Army Commander
Constantine Chiwenga said the first priority of disaster
mangement is the protection of people most at risk and that
second priority is the protection of critical resource systems on
which communities depend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
