<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Denies Detention of Japanese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's judicial authority
today accused Japan's press of filing "baseless" reports,
categorically denying that Lebanon detained any Japanese, not to
mention any alleged members of the "Red Amy."
</P>
<P>
Adnan Addoum, the state prosecutor, stressed that no Japanese
had been arrested by the Lebanese security forces.
</P>
<P>
At the end of a meeting with a Japanese security
delegation, Addoum announced that he received a report from the
country's security authorities that they had not taken into
custody any Japanese citizen in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"During investigations with a number of Palestinians over
certain cases, the Palestinians confessed that there were
foreigners cooperating with them," Addoum told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"These foreigners were captured, but among them was not a
Japanese," the state prosecutor clarified.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, an official in the Japanese
embassy in Beirut denied today that his government has received
"anything official" from the Lebanese side on the detention of
members of the "Red Army."
</P>
<P>
Tokyo's newspapers reported last week that Lebanon arrested
five members of the "Red Army," and they even published the
names and pictures of those persons. Japanese Prime Ministry
reportedly confirmed the reports.
</P>
<P>
A silence observed by the Lebanese government deepened
speculations in both Beirut and Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese papers also said that those detained in Lebanon
included Kozo Okamoto, 49, who had been sentenced to life
imprisonment in Israel for his role in the May 1972 shootout in
Tel Aviv's Lodd airport in which 24 people were killed, and was
released in May 1985 as part of a prisoner swap between Israel
and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The radical "Red Army," founded in 1971, was accused of
involvement in a series of terrorist activities in the Middle
East in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 Japanese journalists arrived in the Lebanese
capital in the past week in order to cover what they
regarded an event attractive for their audience back home.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo sent a two-men security delegation to help Lebanon
conduct the investigation, but the Japanese embassy complained
that the Lebanese government shrugged off the help.
</P>
<P>
Local political observers hoped that a "diplomatic
embarrassment" resulted from the event would not damp efforts of
the cash-hungry government led by Prime Minister Rafik Hariri to
draw financial aid from Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
