<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen, Albright Hold Talks in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen told visiting US Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright here today that China is willing to have more
dialogues and cooperation with the United States.
</P>
<P>
China hopes that the US side will strictly observe the
principles set in the three Sino-US joint communiques, and settle
the Taiwan question in a careful and proper way, in order to
maintain the momentum of improvement and development in bilateral
relations and a favorable environment for their cooperation in the
international affairs, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Qian made the statement during his talks with Albright at the
Diaoyutai Guesthouse this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral ties have seen progress recently, Qian noted, Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and US President Bill Clinton will exchange
state visits in 1997 and 1998, and US Vice-President Al Gore is
expected to visit China next month at the invitation of Chinese
Premier Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, he said, there are opportunities for further
improving and advancing China-US relations.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two foreign ministers also discussed
other issues of common interests including China's accession to
the World Trade Organization, non-proliferation of weapons, and
the Hong Kong issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
