<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright on US Policy Toward China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Visiting US Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said here today that the US is willing to see a
prosperous, stable and safe China and to make concerted efforts
with the Chinese side to broaden bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Albright made the remarks here this afternoon when she was
received by Chinese leaders Jiang Zemin and Li Peng and held talks
with Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen.
</P>
<P>
According to Chinese diplomats present at the meetings and
talks, Albright reaffirmed that the US government will continue to
commit itself to the "One China" policy and principles enshrined
in the three US-Chinese joint communiques.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States signed the Shanghai Joint
Communique in 1972, the joint communique on the establishment of
diplomatic relations in 1978 and another communique in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that the US and China are two major countries in
the world and they face a shared task in maintaining world peace
and stability, and therefore, the US has always viewed its ties
with China as that among the most important ones.
</P>
<P>
She said that President Clinton has repeatedly said that he
will further advance the US-Chinese relations during his second
term so as to build a partnership of cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that 25 years ago the two countries published the
Shanghai Communique out of their shared strategic interests and
that although the world situation has greatly changed since then,
the US and China have enjoyed sound cooperation for they have much
in common.
</P>
<P>
However, she said, differences between the US and China
remain. It is very important for the two countries to narrow their
difference through more high-level dialogues and exchanges, she
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
