<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Makes New Appeal for Ending of Hostility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- France today described the need
to end hostilities in Zaire as "urgent" and reaffirmed its
"active" support for a five-point peace plan for Zaire, which was
unanimously adopted by the United Nations Security Council last
week.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said that
France considers as "extremely preoccupying the resurgence of
fightings in Zaire in the course of the past few days."
</P>
<P>
Zaire's Tutsi-led rebels led by Laurent-Desire Kabila took last
weekend the town of Kalima in South Kivu, which is some 100
kilometers east of the strategic city of Kindu, after Zairean
government forces looted and abandoned the city.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry spokesman said that officials of
the European Union countries will discuss the situation in Zaire
during their session of the EU council of general affairs to be
held in Brussels later this week.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. five-point peace plan for Zaire calls for an immediate
ceasing of hostilities, the withdrawal of all foreign forces,
including mercenaries, and reaffirmation of respect for the
national sovereignty and territorial integrity of Zaire and other
states of the region.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for the guarantee of security of refugees and
displaced people and access of humanitarian aid to them, and a
rapid and peaceful solution to the crisis through dialogue,
elections and holding of an international conference on the peace,
security and development of the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
The author of the peace plan, Algerian diplomat Mohamed
Sahnoun, who is representative of the United Nations and the
Organization of African Unity to the Great Lakes region, will
attend the EU session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
