<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Urged to Use Euro Alongside Pound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Britain should adopt a
two-stage approach to the European Monetary Union (EMU) by making
the euro, the single European currency, legal tender alongside the
pound, according to the Adam Smith Institute.
</P>
<P>
In a report published here today, the institute proposed a dual
currency system for transactions of more than 10 pounds (about 16
U.S. dollars), arguing it would solve the British government's
dilemma over the single currency.
</P>
<P>
This would allow the euro to circulate freely in Britain,
giving British business and citizens access to the single
currency.
</P>
<P>
Madsen Pirie, president of the institute, said, "If the euro is
indeed built upon the sand of fudged criteria, it might well float
down against the pound after its launch."
</P>
<P>
"The greatest advantage of all is that it would allow us to
test the quality of the euro," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Pirie admitted that the proposal was likely to be
rejected by the country's retailers and industry, which would face
the high costs handling two currencies simultaneously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nairobi Varsity Ordered to close Indefinitely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Nairobi University was today
ordered to close indefinitely following two-day protests over the
suspected murder of a student leader by grieving students.
</P>
<P>
Solomon Muruli, a third-year student of the Nairobi
University, was burnt to death in a mysterious explosion on
Sunday morning at his Kikuyu campus, about 30 kilometers from the
Nairobi city center.
</P>
<P>
following his death, university students went on the rampage
last night and today, and have taken to streets lighting fires,
hijacking buses and stoning cars and shop windows.
</P>
<P>
Muruli, the Vice-Chairman of the university's Education
Students Association, died barely a week after he received a note
reportedly threatening him with death.
</P>
<P>
Two months ago, Muruli was abducted by unknown people who
allegedly tortured him for five days before abandoning him in a
church compound in Kiambu district.
</P>
<P>
On December 31 of last year, he was reportedly arrested in the
port city of Mombasa by plain-clothes policemen who accused him
of being a member of the unregistered Safina political party.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the grieving university students last night, Vice
Chancellor Francis Gichaga appealed for calm and promised to set
up a committee to investigate the matter with all seriousness.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government sent out large numbers of anti-riot
police to control the situation when hundreds of irate students
moved into the city center and others barricaded the University
Way/Uhuru Highway round-about and then set about stoning
motorists along State House Road and Uhuru Highway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
