<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Release 405 Prisoners on Liberation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait will set free a
total of 405 prisoners Tuesday morning at the 6th anniversary of
Kuwait's liberation from the Iraqi troops' seven-month
occupation in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Interior Minister Sheikh Mohammed Khaled Al-Sabah
said in an announcement that the decision was made after
receiving an Amiri amnesty today.
</P>
<P>
He said the amnesty which was issued by Kuwaiti Amir Sheikh
Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah on the occasion of the National Day and
the liberation anniversary, covered 12 prisoners convicted in
"state security" cases, including 10 Jordanians and two
Kuwaitis.
</P>
<P>
A total of 34 Jordanians have been imprisoned in Kuwait for
supporting the Iraqi occupying forces in 1990.
</P>
<P>
They received visits by family members on January 20 in a
three-day trip arranged by the International Committee of the
Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Mohammed said the amnesty also included the reduction
of sentences to 590 other prisoners.
</P>
<P>
He said the relatives of the prisoners to be released had
been informed and authorities concerned were making efforts to
ensure the release of the prisoners without delay.
</P>
</TEXT>
