<HEADLINE> Mozambique Urges International Flood Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Foreign Minister
Leonardo Simao today met several foreign envoys based here,
calling for immediate relief aid to alleviate the impact caused
by recent flooding in the country.
</P>
<P>
Simao said among the most needed relief are seeds, farm
tools, food and medicine. He also urged foreign aid to help
rehabilitate the roads and bridges damaged by the flooding of the
rivers of Zambeze, Buzi and Pungue.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, President Joaquim Chissano donated a month's salary
to victims of the disaster while paying an inspecting tour by air
to some of the flooded areas in central Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Chissano also delivered gratitude to the rescue teams
dispatched by the South African and Zimbabwean governments, who
have so far saved over 1,400 people from the floods.
</P>
<P>
Over 500,000 residents in the provinces of Sofala, Tete,
Manica and Zambezia were affected by the floods. 
</P>
