<HEADLINE> Rotary Members Pledge to Crack Social Hard Nuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Rotary International 1997
conference delegates concluded their three-day meetings here today
with a pledge to help solve the humanitarian problems of Middle East
and Mediterranean countries.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 601 Rotary International members from 36 countries
affirmed their full commitment to principles of the club, the
non-governmental group set up in 1905 providing social services
through self-efforts.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released at the closing session, the Rotary
members pledged to serve the society, fight social problems,
further the club's humanitarian services and to uproot polio by
the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Rotary's priority is granted to projects that crack social
hard nuts such as violence, drug addiction, aids, starvation,
illiteracy and pollution, it said.
</P>
<P>
Rotary Club President Luis Vicente Giay, addressing the closing
session, said the widening membership base and activities of the
Club in the Middle East will add to the projects and achievements
geared to promote Rotary services towards humanity.
</P>
<P>
Luis Vicente Giay called for coordinating efforts to attain the
targeted growth of the club's membership and to serve the region's
interests.
</P>
<P>
He affirmed the necessity of enhancing the capabilities of
youths so that they may be able to challenge the future and
stressed the need for the eradication of diseases, mainly polio,
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Rotary foundation reportedly allocates 90 million
U.S. dollars annually for international humanitarian programs,
with particular focus on youth services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
