<HEADLINE> Turkey Seizes 22 Kilograms of Pure Heroin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Turkish gendarme police this
evening seized 22 kilograms of pure heroin in an operation
against the drug trafficking in Van province bordering Iran, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the gendarme police stopped a car in
Gurpimar town of Van and found the heroin hidden in the vehicle
worth about 800,000 U.S. dollars on the market.
</P>
<P>
The gendarme police detained two suspected drug smugglers,
said the agency.
</P>
<P>
Anatolia also reported that in other developments, Turkish
police had confiscated 2.3 kilograms of heroin in anti-drug
operations in Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
According to Turkish security authorities, in 1996, the
Turkish police seized 4.4 tonnes of heroin, accounting for 40
percent of the world's total haul, 12.3 tonnes of hashish, 223
kilograms of opium, 13 kilograms of cocaine and 1,157 kilograms
of base morphine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
