<HEADLINE> Cyprus Protests Against Air-space Violation by Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has protested against
Turkish military planes' reconnaissance flight over its air-space.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Yiannakis Cassoulides said today at his
daily press briefing that Cyprus' Permanent Representative to
the U.N. has been instructed to make representations against
repeated violations of Cypriot air-space by Turkish reconnaissance
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was commenting on reports that two Turkish
military planes made reconnaissance flights over the sea area,
off the southern and western coastal towns of Limassol and
Paphos and island of Rhodes between Cyprus and Greece last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to a Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation (CyBC) report,
the two Turkish RF-4 planes, especially used for photographing,
were located by Cyprus National Guard radars.
</P>
<P>
CyBC said the two Turkish military aircraft were trying to
locate and photograph strategic places of importance to the
joint defense pact, agreed between the governments of Cyprus and
Greece in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Cassoulides also made special reference to the most recent
arrest of a young Greek Cypriot by the Turkish Cypriot side,
accusing it of creating tension on the island.
</P>
<P>
Sotiris Louca Siderenos, who was said to lost his way and
crossed into the Turkish-controlled northern areas, was apprehended
by Turkish Cypriot regime last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman expressed the hope that the Turkish side
would show the necessary political will for a successful outcome
of the U.N.-sponsored indirect military dialog between the
National Guard and the Turkish forces.
</P>
<P>
The dialog was conducted following a tension on this
eastern Mediterranean island since last Summer.
</P>
<P>
Four Greek Cypriots have been killed and a Turkish solider
was murdered since last June along the U.N.-controlled buffer
zone.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been partitioned since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
