<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese People Recall Deng's Merits in Economic Reform (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xie Shijie, secretary of the Sichuan Provincial Communist Party
Committee, said that Deng Xiaoping had been back to his hometown
province twice since the country's economic reform, and every time
he would stress the importance of economic development.
</P>
<P>
Guided by his economic policy, the local GDP of Sichuan in 1996
was about four times that of 1980, Xie said.
</P>
<P>
Deng Xiaoping also told people in his hometown to emancipate
their minds in bolstering agricultural and industrial production
so as to make the people have better lives.
</P>
<P>
In some old revolutionary bases, many local people have shaken
off poverty, thanks to Deng Xiaoping's thinking of "poverty is not
equal to socialism."
</P>
<P>
Outlining the country's modernization drive, Deng Xiaoping
depicted a three-step development strategy: China's per capita GNP
in 1990 doubles that in 1980 to make the people have adequate food
and clothing; per capita GNP by the end of the century doubles
again on the basis of 1990 figure to make the people lead a
comfortable life; by the middle of next century, per capita GNP
reaches the level in advanced countries to basicly achieve
modernization.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with Deng's economic outline, China has been
carrying out economic reforms to establish a socialist market
economy and to open wider to the outside world, so as to achieve
sustained, fast and sound growth of the national economy, said
Chen Jinhua, minister in charge of the State Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
The goal of quadrupling the per capita GNP, which was planned
for the first two development steps, has been achieved ahead of
schedule. China's comprehensive national power is strengthened and
people's living standards are greatly improved, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Just at this time, Deng Xiaoping passed away. Many officials
and the masses said that although Deng could not see his grand
goals fulfilled, the Chinese people can surely accomplish them by
next century under the leadership of the CPC Central Committee
with Jiang Zemin at the core.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's FM on C'Wealth Meeting in Botswana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Foreign Minister
Stan Mudenge said today 18 African leaders will hold a two-day
Commonwealth roundtable meeting on Wednesday at Kasane game lodge
in northern Botswana to discuss democracy in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mudenge, who chairs the Commonwealth Ministerial Action Group
on the Harare Declaration (CMAG), said the group, which met in
London early this month, resolved that Nigeria, Sierra Leone and
Gambia should speed up moves to embrace democratic principles.
</P>
<P>
He said following its visits to the three countries, the group
discovered that the countries had partially implemented the
recommendations of the Harare Declaration, with violations of
human rights still being evident in most of the countries.
</P>
<P>
He said while Nigeria, which was suspended from the
Commonwealth in 1995, had made great strides in improving its
human rights record, it still continued to detain opponents
without trial.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial group, he said, also noted that the continued
exclusion of a significant part of the Gambian civilians from the
political life of the country continued to be detrimental to the
cause of democracy in that country.
</P>
<P>
''In the meantime, the group welcomed the conclusion of the
electoral phase of the transition in Gambia marked by the
parliamentary elections of January 2 1997,'' said Mudenge.
</P>
<P>
CMAG was formed in 1995 as a Commonwealth mechanism for
dealing with serious or persistent violations of the Harare
Declaration principles arrived at in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
