<DOCNO> XIE19970225.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-24 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian and Lebanese Presidents Agree on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias
Hrawi and Syrian President Hafez Assad have agreed that their
countries' peace negotiations with Israel should be resumed from
where they were suspended.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Lebanese National News Agency said this evening
that the Lebanese-Syrian summit, which was held in Damascus
Sunday, reiterated peace positions of the two countries and their
 continuous coordinations.
</P>
<P>
This was the first official comment made by Lebanon on
the details of the Summit meeting, the first since October.
</P>
<P>
"The Lebanese-Syrian summit reiterated the Lebanese-Syrian
positions toward the Middle East peace process and their
coordination of positions over any new developments," the LNNA
said.
</P>
<P>
"The Lebanese and Syrian presidents stressed a necessity to
resume the negotiations from where they were stopped and not
to return to the zero point," the agency noted.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Syria and Israel, which had been held
at the Wye Plantation, Maryland in the United States, were
indefinitely suspended last February amid a wave of bombings
in Israel, only three months before the Israeli Labor government
stepped down.
</P>
<P>
The two heads of state agreed that a re-start of the
peace negotiations from the beginning "is totally unacceptable,
and it contradicts the international practice," the LNNA added.
</P>
<P>
Damascus and Beirut feared that the right-wing Israeli
government of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu would use the
Hebron agreement, signed not long ago between Israel and the
Palestinian National Authority, as a tool for exerting pressures
upon the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The LNNA reported as well that the Syrian-Lebanese summit
dealt "with the bilateral relations and the domestic situation
in Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
The Summit came only one day after a meeting in Damascus
between Assad and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarad, who is
expected to meet U.S. President Bill Clinton in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Syria said that former Israeli Labor government had promised a
withdrawal from Syria's Golan Heights, but Netanyahu argued that
he would not be obliged by any unwritten commitment.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon upholds an adherence to an interlock of the
Lebanese and Syrian tracks and refuses to talk any peace
settlement with Israel before a tangible progress is achieved
between Syria and the Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
