<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Gov't, Opposition Fail to Reconcile Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the ruling coalition
and the opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) failed to narrow
their difference over the controversial tax reform plan in
negotiations today, but agreed to continue their talks later this
week.
</P>
<P>
SPD leader Oskar Lafontaine said after the three-hour talks
this afternoon, "There was no movement towards reconciliation."
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated his party's rejection of an increase in the
value-added tax (VAT) as proposed by the government to offset the
revenue shortfall induced by the tax reform.
</P>
<P>
Aimed at bolstering business competitiveness and job creation,
tax reform has become the German government's top domestic policy
priority and its main recipe to curb unemployment, which stands at
4.66 billion, the highest since 1933.
</P>
<P>
Under its proposed reform plan, the government wants to cut
income taxes to 15 percent for low-wage earners and 39 percent for
people with high incomes instead of the current marginal rates
ranging from 25.9 percent to 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to government estimates, the income tax cuts, along
with other cuts in corporate tax rates, would leave a shortfall in
state revenue of 44 billion Deutsche marks (26.3 billion U.S.
dollars) which the government wants to reduce to 30 billion marks
(17.9 billion dollars) by raising the 15 percent VAT to 16
percent.
</P>
<P>
Apart from its opposition to VAT increase, the SPD has also
said that while it backs cutting income tax for low-wage earners,
it wants to leave the 53 percent rate intact for the rich.
</P>
<P>
The government needs to strike a compromise with the SPD if the
reform plan is to survive the upper house of the German parliament,
Bundesrat, where the SPD controls a majority.
</P>
<P>
Given the wide difference between the government and the SPD,
German media expect a marathon bargaining between the two sides,
possibly until April or May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
