<P>
Yiannakis Cassoulides, the spokesman, told reporters that "the
British believe that Cyprus should be demilitarized as part of a
solution."
</P>
<P>
President Clerides' demilitarization proposal has been welcomed
abroad, the spokesman said, adding that it has not been
dealt with so far due to Turkey's "utter rejection."
</P>
<P>
Cassoulides made clear that President Clerides' proposal does
not concern British bases troops but those of the Cyprus
Republic's National Guard and the Turkish occupation army.
</P>
<P>
Britain, the former colonial power, has retained two
sovereign military bases on the island under the 1960 Treaty on
Establishment of the Cyprus Republic.
</P>
<P>
President Clerides' demilitarization proposal, which was
submitted to former U.N. Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali
in December 1993, provides for the disbanding of the Cyprus
National Guard, the handing over of its weapons and equipment to
U.N. Peace-Keeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP).
</P>
<P>
In return, the proposal also calls for the withdrawal of
the Turkish forces and the disbanding of the Turkish Cypriot
armed forces, the handing over of their weapons and military
equipment to the custody of UNFICYP.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey militarily
intervened and occupied the northern third of the island
following an Athens-backed coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
