<HEADLINE> Indian Army General Visits Peace-keepers in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Deputy Chief of Staff of the
Indian Army, General Ved Brakash Malik, said today he is
optimistic about Angola's peace prospect while visiting India's
peacekeeping forces operating in the country.
</P>
<P>
Malik, who is wrapping up his three-day tour of Angola, made
the remarks here after discussing the peace process with the
United Nations special envoy in Angola, Blondin Beye.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,083 Indian troops, military engineers and
observers are currently in the southern African country, among
the 7,000-strong U.N. peacekeeping forces operating in Angola.
</P>
