<HEADLINE> Camerounian Premier to Attend African C'Wealth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Premier Peter Mafani Musonge
will leave here on Tuesday for Gaborone, Botswana as head of the
Camerounian delegation to attend the roundtable of African heads
of government of Commonwealth on democracy and good governance.
</P>
<P>
The local radio reported here today that a group of experts
from 18 Commonwealth African countries started a meeting in
Gaborone today to prepare for the roundtable summit.
</P>
<P>
Cameroun is a bilingual country in Africa. French and English
are the country's official languages, a legacy of the
colonization by both Britain and France from 1916 until the
1960s. English, however, is only marginally spoken - mainly in
the two west provinces of the country.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Cameroun became the 52nd member of the Commonwealth.
It has lost no time in exploring the practical benefits of
belonging to the organization.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth has helped for more than thirty development
projects in Cameroun involving training programs, concern
national education, industrial and commercial development,
environment and forestry, public service and administrative
reform, agricultural projects, and social and women's affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
