<HEADLINE> Yemen Denies Intention to Normalize Relations With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- An official of the Yemeni
Ministry of Foreign Affairs refuted today reports of some media
on the intention of Yemen and Israel to open reciprocal interests
offices in the other side.
</P>
<P>
In a statement today to the Yemeni news agency, the official
said the reports were absolutely unfounded.
</P>
<P>
He said that there would be no normalization with Israel
before the establishment of just and comprehensive peace in the
Middle East, the restoration of legitimate Arab rights and
Israeli withdrawal from the occupied Arab territories in
Palestine, the Golan and south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, Mohamed Ahmed Luqman,
Yemeni Ambassador to Egypt and Permanent Delegate to the
Cairo-based Arab League, has also categorically denied reports about
the establishment of diplomatic relations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Egyptian Middle East News Agency, the
ambassador refuted reports about a meeting today between Yemeni
Deputy Premier and Foreign Minister Abdul Karim al-Iriyani and an
Israeli official.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy had recently been quoted
by Israel Radio as saying that Israel and Yemen would soon open
interests offices in the other country.
</P>
<P>
Levy also revealed that Israeli officials had met with the
Yemeni foreign minister to discuss the matter, though declining
to specify when and where such meeting had taken place.  
</P>
</TEXT>
